abstract: The titular illness is not the only disorder in the family of a Vietnam veteran who is recovering from a stroke.
snippet: The titular illness is not the only disorder in the family of a Vietnam veteran who is recovering from a stroke.
lead_paragraph: Mike Testin has dozens of cinematography credits, but the psychological thriller “Dementia” is his first try at directing a feature. You’d never know it, though. It’s an assured, deftly acted movie that builds its creepiness slowly and keeps its secrets well hidden till the end.

headline.main: Review: ‘Dementia,’ Where Misery Is Company
headline.print_headline: Review: ‘Dementia,’ Where Misery Is Company

abstract: Hillary Clinton proposed spending $2 billion a year on Alzheimer’s research, more than double the amount now set aside, and would pay for it through tax code changes.
snippet: Hillary Clinton proposed spending $2 billion a year on Alzheimer’s research, more than double the amount now set aside, and would pay for it through tax code changes.
lead_paragraph: This past fall, Hillary Clinton met Keith F. Thompson, a librarian in New Hampshire who explained that he couldn’t afford full-time care for his 84-year-old mother who has Alzheimer’s. Grasping Mrs. Clinton’s hands, Mr. Thompson said that he had to take his mother to work with him.

headline.main: Hillary Clinton Proposes Doubling Spending on Alzheimer’s Research
headline.print_headline: A Proposal by Clinton to Combat Alzheimeru2019s

abstract: Tube feeding has become commonplace, especially for patients with dementia, but it causes them pain and provides no benefits.
snippet: Tube feeding has become commonplace, especially for patients with dementia, but it causes them pain and provides no benefits.
lead_paragraph: THE practice of forced feeding has been highlighted by its use on hunger strikers in Guantánamo Bay and, more recently, in Israel, where a vigorous debate about the ethics of such a practice is taking place. But you don’t have to be in prison to have a feeding tube jammed up your nose. Millions of elderly Americans are fed through tubes despite a lack of substantial evidence pointing to any clinical benefit.

abstract: There are three common traps that the proxy decision-maker should be aware of in trying to guide health care at the end of someone else’s life.
snippet: There are three common traps that the proxy decision-maker should be aware of in trying to guide health care at the end of someone else’s life.
lead_paragraph: Of the many factors that affect the experience of dying, the one that patients and families often have the greatest control over is making decisions that are in the patient’s best interest. I recently participated in research on barriers to quality end-of-life care as part of a study released today in the Journal of Palliative Medicine. Some of the hurdles we identified, such as financial limitations or access to top doctors, may require societal change. But I am focusing here on the personal part of the puzzle that all patients, whatever their socioeconomic status, should have the potential to influence.

headline.main: Pitfalls for Proxies

abstract: Susan Schneider Williams laid the blame for her husband’s death not on depression, but on Lewy body dementia, a disease that is often misdiagnosed.
snippet: Susan Schneider Williams laid the blame for her husband’s death not on depression, but on Lewy body dementia, a disease that is often misdiagnosed.
lead_paragraph: For the first time in more than a year, the widow of the actor Robin Williams is speaking publicly about the circumstances that preceded Mr. Williams’s death, and sharing details about a disease he had when he died.

abstract: Maria Dearmas, 58, went missing for three days after being discharged alone from a hospital that should have known she had schizophrenia and dementia.
snippet: Maria Dearmas, 58, went missing for three days after being discharged alone from a hospital that should have known she had schizophrenia and dementia.
lead_paragraph: Around 8:30 on the morning of Nov. 1, the Sunday that the New York City Marathon was being run, an ambulance went to a building on East 111th Street in Manhattan and picked up a woman with bad pains in her belly. Medics took her 14 blocks south, to the emergency room at Metropolitan Hospital Center. The woman, Maria Dearmas, 58, was a frequent visitor to Metropolitan for a range of miseries.

abstract: Brain injuries have turned boxing into a sport many see as too brutal. Perhaps football will fall into the same category for the same reason one day.
snippet: Brain injuries have turned boxing into a sport many see as too brutal. Perhaps football will fall into the same category for the same reason one day.
lead_paragraph: The sweet science. That was the lofty sobriquet assigned to boxing long ago by devoted followers with a romantic flair. But there came a time when the fight game’s hold on the American spirit began to loosen, when it stood widely condemned as plain brutal.

abstract: An Annals of Internal Medicine paper reports that the money needed to treat dementia in a patient’s final five years is greater than for heart disease and cancer.
snippet: An Annals of Internal Medicine paper reports that the money needed to treat dementia in a patient’s final five years is greater than for heart disease and cancer.
lead_paragraph: Three diseases, leading killers of Americans, often involve long periods of decline before death. Two of them — heart disease and cancer — usually require expensive drugs, surgeries and hospitalizations. The third, dementia, has no effective treatments to slow its course.

abstract: My parents’ approach to death reflected their marriage: He always needed control, while she let events shape her.
snippet: My parents’ approach to death reflected their marriage: He always needed control, while she let events shape her.
lead_paragraph: My parents each took an approach to the end of life that was indicative of the way they lived their lives.

abstract: Gen. Efraín Ríos Montt, who came to power in a 1982 coup, is accused of leading the persecution of the Maya Ixil Indians.
snippet: Gen. Efraín Ríos Montt, who came to power in a 1982 coup, is accused of leading the persecution of the Maya Ixil Indians.
lead_paragraph: MEXICO CITY — A Guatemalan court ruled on Tuesday that the former dictator Gen. Efraín Ríos Montt must face a new genocide trial in the persecution of the Maya Ixil Indians during his rule, but agreed to hold it behind closed doors because he has dementia.

abstract: The findings do not explain why women’s mental capacities tend to decline faster, but could alter the way drug trials are conducted, experts said.
snippet: The findings do not explain why women’s mental capacities tend to decline faster, but could alter the way drug trials are conducted, experts said.
lead_paragraph: Women who develop slight but detectable deficits in memory and mental acuity late in life tend to decline faster than men with mild impairment, researchers reported on Tuesday.

headline.main: Dementia Develops Faster in Women Than in Men, Study Suggests
headline.print_headline: After First Signs, Dementia Develops Faster in Women Than in Men, Study Suggests

abstract: A brisk walk may be all it takes to help improve our ability to think as we age, but more may not be better, according to a new study of exercise and cognition.
snippet: A brisk walk may be all it takes to help improve our ability to think as we age, but more may not be better, according to a new study of exercise and cognition.
lead_paragraph: A small amount of exercise may improve our ability to think as we age, but more may not be better, according to a new study of exercise and cognition.

abstract: Henry Rayhons last week was acquitted of charges that he sexually abused his wife, who has Alzheimer’s, prompting a national discussion about consent between partners.
snippet: Henry Rayhons last week was acquitted of charges that he sexually abused his wife, who has Alzheimer’s, prompting a national discussion about consent between partners.
lead_paragraph: Henry Rayhons, a farmer and former Iowa state representative, was acquitted last week of charges that he had sexually abused his wife, who had Alzheimer’s disease. He had been accused of having sex with her in a nursing home on May 23, 2014, eight days after staff members told him at a care conference that they considered her cognitively unable to consent.

abstract: Barney Norris’s play “Visitors” has returned to London for a weeklong run at the Bush Theater.
snippet: Barney Norris’s play “Visitors” has returned to London for a weeklong run at the Bush Theater.
lead_paragraph: LONDON — For Edie and Arthur, an English couple who have lived together on a farm for some 40 years, life’s final horizon seems to have reared up with an alarming suddenness. The days and years have passed by uneventfully for this contented and very settled pair, for whom even holidays were rare events. But now Edie’s mind has begun to falter. She can’t move very well, but more distressingly, words don’t come as easily as they once did, and when they do, they may not be the ones intended.

headline.main: Fusillades Piercing a Fog of Dementia
headline.print_headline: Fusillades Piercing a Fog of Dementia

abstract: Some wonder if a directive to hasten death by withholding “ordinary means of nutrition and hydration” should apply to a person who can’t remember it.
snippet: Some wonder if a directive to hasten death by withholding “ordinary means of nutrition and hydration” should apply to a person who can’t remember it.
lead_paragraph: DEDHAM, Mass. — Jerome Medalie keeps his advance directive hanging in a plastic sleeve in his front hall closet, as his retirement community recommends. That’s where the paramedics will look if someone calls 911.

lead_paragraph: “You try to think about a lot of things before you make a commitment,” Eric Sacks says during a documentary about his wife, “but you don’t think about something like this.”

headline.main: Can People With Dementia Have a Sex Life?

abstract: New figures show the global cost of dementia could reach $1 trillion dollars by 2018. As Hayley Platt report one altzeimers organisation is calling on businesses to help.

headline.main: Dementia costs could top $1 trln by 2018

abstract: New figures show the global cost of dementia could reach $1 trillion dollars by 2018. As Hayley Platt report one alzheimer's organisation is calling on businesses to help.

headline.main: Dementia costs could top $1 trln by 2018

abstract: New figures show the global cost of dementia could reach $1 trillion dollars by 2018. As Hayley Platt report one Alzheimer's organisation is calling on businesses to help.

lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Even before Ronald Reagan became the oldest elected president, his mental state was a political issue. His adversaries often suggested his penchant for contradictory statements, forgetting names and seeming absent-mindedness could be linked to dementia.

abstract: It’s another rising reality for an aging population: people over age 75 providing care for partners, siblings, friends and even parents.
snippet: It’s another rising reality for an aging population: people over age 75 providing care for partners, siblings, friends and even parents.
lead_paragraph: Gail Schwartz wants to keep her 85-year-old husband out of a nursing home as long as she can, but it isn’t easy.

headline.main: More Caregivers Are No Spring Chickens Themselves
headline.print_headline: Caregivers Who Are No Spring Chickens

abstract: A guide that asks about what matters to you, not what’s the matter with you.
snippet: A guide that asks about what matters to you, not what’s the matter with you.
lead_paragraph: I was 25 when I flew home for my father’s last birthday. His cancer had returned and he would die three months later at the age of 57. What I remember most about that weekend was the large rectangular gift box he opened. My mother had bought him a new suitcase.

abstract: Barred by a settlement from practicing journalism about the entertainment industry online, Ms. Finke is writing fiction for her new website, Hollywood Dementia.
snippet: Barred by a settlement from practicing journalism about the entertainment industry online, Ms. Finke is writing fiction for her new website, Hollywood Dementia.
lead_paragraph: LOS ANGELES — If Nikki Finke had not been a journalist, she says she could have been a detective. The police in New York, where she reported decades ago, used to show her “these gruesome homicide photos,” she said, to try to freak her out. Instead she found them fascinating.

abstract: Data from the largest analysis to date of amyloid plaques showed they can appear 20 or 30 years before dementia symptoms.
snippet: Data from the largest analysis to date of amyloid plaques showed they can appear 20 or 30 years before dementia symptoms.
lead_paragraph: The largest analysis to date of amyloid plaques in people’s brains confirms that the presence of the substance can help predict who will develop Alzheimer’s and determine who has the disease.

abstract: The Ethicists consider when it’s worth taking away a loved one’s autonomy.
snippet: The Ethicists consider when it’s worth taking away a loved one’s autonomy.
lead_paragraph: I believe my 86-year-old spouse is in the early stages of dementia. He won’t see a doctor. I asked for some advice in an online caretaker’s forum, and a couple of people told me to tell my spouse some lie about why he’s going to the doctor and then have the doctor give him a cognitive test. I think it would be unethical to ever trick someone into doing something, but if he is slipping into this disease, he may be doing all he can to protect himself from knowing it. Is it ethical to lie to someone in order to help him? NAME WITHHELD

abstract: The case of a Wisconsin man with A.L.S. who lawyers argued had dementia and was not responsible in the shooting deaths of his wife and sister-in-law has raised concerns about A.L.S. patients being branded violent.
snippet: The case of a Wisconsin man with A.L.S. who lawyers argued had dementia and was not responsible in the shooting deaths of his wife and sister-in-law has raised concerns about A.L.S. patients being branded violent.
lead_paragraph: In what experts say is likely the first legal decision of its kind, a jury in Wisconsin has found a former sheriff’s deputy not legally responsible in the shooting deaths of his wife and her sister because he has amyotrophic lateral sclerosis, or Lou Gehrig’s disease.

abstract: It’s insane that we spend so much on health care and so little on research.
snippet: It’s insane that we spend so much on health care and so little on research.
lead_paragraph: MCLEAN, Va. — NO one who lived through the 1990s would have suspected that one day people would look back on the period as a golden age of bipartisan cooperation. But in some important ways, it was. Amid the policy fights that followed the Republican victories of 1994, President Bill Clinton and the new majorities in Congress reached one particularly good deal: doubling the budget for the National Institutes of Health.

abstract: Studies show that the ability to perform math problems, as well as handling money matters, are typically one of the first skills to decline in diseases like Alzheimer’s.
snippet: Studies show that the ability to perform math problems, as well as handling money matters, are typically one of the first skills to decline in diseases like Alzheimer’s.
lead_paragraph: WHEN Helen Clark brought her father-in-law, then 83, to the doctor last year, she knew his mind was slowing, but a mental status exam confirmed it. He knew the year, where he lived and the name of the president. But when the doctor asked him to count backward from 100, subtracting seven from each number — 100, 93, 86, 79 — a look of confusion washed over his face.

abstract: Henry Rayhons was accused of sexually abusing his wife in a nursing home after staff members told him she had become cognitively unable to give consent.
snippet: Henry Rayhons was accused of sexually abusing his wife in a nursing home after staff members told him she had become cognitively unable to give consent.
lead_paragraph: An Iowa jury on Wednesday found Henry Rayhons not guilty of charges that he sexually abused his wife, an Alzheimer’s patient, by having sex with her in a nursing home after staff members told him she was cognitively unable to give consent.

abstract: Investigators are recommending that Medicare officials take immediate action to reduce unnecessary prescriptions to older Americans with dementia.
snippet: Investigators are recommending that Medicare officials take immediate action to reduce unnecessary prescriptions to older Americans with dementia.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Federal investigators say they have found evidence of widespread overuse of psychiatric drugs by older Americans with Alzheimer’s disease, and are recommending that Medicare officials take immediate action to reduce unnecessary prescriptions.

abstract: The best efforts at reform follow the principles of palliative care: focusing on the patient’s comfort and pleasure.
snippet: The best efforts at reform follow the principles of palliative care: focusing on the patient’s comfort and pleasure.
lead_paragraph: Speak the words “dementia” and “nursing home,” and you’ve exposed two great fears among people in developed countries, where living until 80 or 90 is increasingly common. Despite efforts to keep frail elders in their own homes, increasing numbers of people with dementia are likely to spend time in a nursing home.
keywords: [{'name': 'subject', 'value': 'Death and Dying', 'rank': 1, 'major': 'N'}, {'name': 'subject', 'value': 'Nursing Homes', 'rank': 2, 'major': 'N'}]
headline.main: Transforming Nursing Home Care

lead_paragraph: “What patients and their families don’t realize is that they are on their own.”

abstract: Ms. Uggams will play a matriarch with dementia and squabbling children.
snippet: Ms. Uggams will play a matriarch with dementia and squabbling children.
lead_paragraph: Leslie Uggams will star in the title role of the New York debut of Colman Domingo’s “Dot,” coming to the Vineyard Theater on Feb. 23. Ms. Uggams, a Tony and Emmy award winner, will return to the New York theater for her first extended run since 2008’s “The First Breeze of Summer.”

abstract: Senator Claire McCaskill of Missouri this week raised concerns about dietary supplements that claim to protect against dementia and Alzheimer’s disease
snippet: Senator Claire McCaskill of Missouri this week raised concerns about dietary supplements that claim to protect against dementia and Alzheimer’s disease
lead_paragraph: A United States Senator this week raised concerns about dietary supplements that claim to protect against dementia and Alzheimer’s disease and urged 15 major companies and retailers to explain why they sell dubious supplements.

headline.main: Alzheimer’s Supplements Targeted by U.S. Senator

abstract: In New Hampshire, Mr. Bush said, “My mother-in-law has dementia and she’s 94 years old.” He added, “She’s a gift from God; she’s the most beautiful woman I’ve ever met.”
snippet: In New Hampshire, Mr. Bush said, “My mother-in-law has dementia and she’s 94 years old.” He added, “She’s a gift from God; she’s the most beautiful woman I’ve ever met.”
lead_paragraph: BEDFORD, N.H. — At an event in Portsmouth, N.H. on Wednesday, Jeb Bush raised his hand, acknowledging that he too had a loved one with Alzheimer’s disease.

abstract: An increase in Silver Alerts, for older adults who go missing, highlights the need for the city to create programs and services for its aging residents, officials say.
snippet: An increase in Silver Alerts, for older adults who go missing, highlights the need for the city to create programs and services for its aging residents, officials say.
lead_paragraph: Alba Sanchez has an alarm in her house in the Bronx that goes off whenever someone opens the front door. For good measure, she has three dogs to bark, not at who is coming in but at who is going out.

abstract: The drug, developed by Biogen Idec, could achieve sales of billions of dollars a year if the results from the small trial are replicated in larger trials.
snippet: The drug, developed by Biogen Idec, could achieve sales of billions of dollars a year if the results from the small trial are replicated in larger trials.
lead_paragraph: An experimental drug for Alzheimer’s disease sharply slowed the decline in mental function in a small clinical trial, researchers reported Friday, reviving hopes for an approach to therapy that until now has experienced repeated failures.

abstract: Ms. Ieng Thirith, the most powerful woman in a brutal regime and Pol Pot’s sister-in-law, was found unfit for trial in 2012 because of dementia.
snippet: Ms. Ieng Thirith, the most powerful woman in a brutal regime and Pol Pot’s sister-in-law, was found unfit for trial in 2012 because of dementia.
lead_paragraph: Ieng Thirith, the sister-in-law and close collaborator of the genocidal Cambodian leader Pol Pot, died on Saturday in Pailin, Cambodia. She was 83.

abstract: While still at the apex of a stellar medical career, Dr. Graboys was found to have Parkinson’s disease. He detailed the stages of his illness in his autobiography.
snippet: While still at the apex of a stellar medical career, Dr. Graboys was found to have Parkinson’s disease. He detailed the stages of his illness in his autobiography.
lead_paragraph: When he was just 5 years old, Thomas Graboys declared that he intended to become a doctor. As a young physician, he visited a nephew serving in the Peace Corps in Mauritania and remained for two months, treating dozens of patients a day.

abstract: The Vikings linebacker went on to become a lawyer and a spokesman for former players who suffer from early onset dementia and other cognitive problems, as he did.
snippet: The Vikings linebacker went on to become a lawyer and a spokesman for former players who suffer from early onset dementia and other cognitive problems, as he did.
lead_paragraph: Fred McNeill, a hard-hitting linebacker who appeared in two Super Bowls with the Minnesota Vikings before becoming a lawyer and a spokesman for former players who suffer from early onset dementia and other cognitive problems, as he did, died on Nov. 3 at his home in Los Angeles. He was 63.

abstract: Florian Zeller’s play has earned acclaim in France and England.
snippet: Florian Zeller’s play has earned acclaim in France and England.
lead_paragraph: Three-time Tony Award winner Frank Langella will be back on Broadway next spring in the title role of “The Father,” a play by Florian Zeller that has earned acclaim in Europe.

abstract: A limitation of studying chronic traumatic encephalopathy, or C.T.E., has been that researchers have been able to detect it only in tissue obtained posthumously.
snippet: A limitation of studying chronic traumatic encephalopathy, or C.T.E., has been that researchers have been able to detect it only in tissue obtained posthumously.
lead_paragraph: One of the limitations of studying chronic traumatic encephalopathy, or C.T.E., the degenerative brain disease linked to repeated head trauma, has been that researchers have been able to detect it only in tissue obtained posthumously.

abstract: A war-scarred man finds comfort in unraveling secrets from his grandmother’s past.
snippet: A war-scarred man finds comfort in unraveling secrets from his grandmother’s past.
lead_paragraph: The literature of war is by its very nature political. If a writer’s sentences are ­personal — what else, really, can they be? — and a writer has trained his lens on a bloody battleground, in reading him we will come to know where he stands, where his passions lie. When it comes to fiction, this passion can often result in ­rhetoric-spouting characters whose sole purpose is to service the author’s ideas. But in “The Illuminations,” the Scottish novelist and critic Andrew O’Hagan has created a story that is both a howl against the war in Afghanistan and the societies that have blindly abetted it, and a multilayered, deeply felt tale of family, loss, memory, art, loyalty, secrecy and forgiveness.

abstract: The name of Shawn Wooden, a former Dolphin and an important advocate of the deal, will most likely be invoked again Monday, when a dozen objections are expected to be filed in court.
snippet: The name of Shawn Wooden, a former Dolphin and an important advocate of the deal, will most likely be invoked again Monday, when a dozen objections are expected to be filed in court.
lead_paragraph: MIRAMAR, Fla. — During his nine years in the N.F.L., Shawn Wooden was a steady, if unspectacular, presence on the field. Selected in the sixth round of the 1996 draft by the Miami Dolphins, he never made it to the Super Bowl, and in all likelihood, he will never be elected to the Pro Football Hall of Fame.

abstract: Starring Catherine Deneuve, Pierre Salvadori’s film depicts an unlikely friendship between an anxious woman and a onetime musician who has hit bottom.
snippet: Starring Catherine Deneuve, Pierre Salvadori’s film depicts an unlikely friendship between an anxious woman and a onetime musician who has hit bottom.
lead_paragraph: Depression, dementia, disillusion — they’re all there in “In the Courtyard,” a gently meandering study of two troubled souls who form a cross-generational bond.

abstract: A deal to resolve a lawsuit by retired athletes wouldn’t have helped Junior Seau or others with chronic traumatic encephalopathy.
snippet: A deal to resolve a lawsuit by retired athletes wouldn’t have helped Junior Seau or others with chronic traumatic encephalopathy.
lead_paragraph: Thanks to the ham-handedness of the National Football League’s Hall of Fame, the inane “deflategate” scandal, which has been the dominant N.F.L. headline this off-season, was pushed to the sidelines this weekend and replaced by a genuinely important issue facing the country’s dominant sports league and its players. That issue is the serious cognitive impairment that appears to affect so many former professional football players.

abstract: Pyle was among the many former N.F.L. players who brought suit against the league for disregarding cognitive dangers resulting from football collisions.
snippet: Pyle was among the many former N.F.L. players who brought suit against the league for disregarding cognitive dangers resulting from football collisions.
lead_paragraph: Mike Pyle, the captain of Yale’s last unbeaten and untied football team and of the 1963 N.F.L. champion Chicago Bears, died at 76 on Wednesday in Highland Park, Ill., after a decade-long battle with dementia, which his family believes may have resulted from the battering he took as an offensive lineman.

abstract: Mr. Pratchett, an accomplished British satirist, was known for his Discworld series. He created wildly imaginative alternative realities in his more than 70 books.
snippet: Mr. Pratchett, an accomplished British satirist, was known for his Discworld series. He created wildly imaginative alternative realities in his more than 70 books.
lead_paragraph: Terry Pratchett, the immensely popular British fantasy novelist whose more than 70 books include the series known as Discworld, died on Thursday at his home near Salisbury, England. He was 66.

abstract: An aging generation must confront its growing need for health care with the looming shortage of geriatric specialists.
snippet: An aging generation must confront its growing need for health care with the looming shortage of geriatric specialists.
lead_paragraph: WE talk a lot these days about what constitutes a good way to die. There’s also much discussion about the art of healthy aging.

abstract: Wendy Wasserstein’s final play is at TheaterWorks in Hartford through Nov. 8.
snippet: Wendy Wasserstein’s final play is at TheaterWorks in Hartford through Nov. 8.
lead_paragraph: Wendy Wasserstein’s rich, moving and witty final play, “Third,” has kicked off the 30th anniversary season at Hartford’s TheaterWorks in superb fashion. With a magnificent company of perfectly cast actors, brilliant direction by TheaterWorks’ producing artistic director, Rob Ruggiero, and a characteristically first-rate design team, this production is emblematic of how and why TheaterWorks has become such an enduring and invaluable Hartford institution.

abstract: Advocates have filed a lawsuit to allow participants in the program, which allows renters 62 and older to lock their rent at the current rate, to renew even if they miss the deadline.
snippet: Advocates have filed a lawsuit to allow participants in the program, which allows renters 62 and older to lock their rent at the current rate, to renew even if they miss the deadline.
lead_paragraph: As New York City officials encourage older tenants to take advantage of an underused program that freezes their rents, they have also been cutting off participants who fail to renew on time, advocates say.

abstract: Roboticists and physicians predict that a new wave of technological advances, including drones, will help older adults stay at home longer.
snippet: Roboticists and physicians predict that a new wave of technological advances, including drones, will help older adults stay at home longer.
lead_paragraph: SAN FRANCISCO — The ranks of older and frail adults are growing rapidly in the developed world, raising alarms about how society is going to help them take care of themselves in their own homes.

abstract: A dispute over Liliane Bettencourt, 92, has riveted France by opening a window on the private lives of the rich and contested.
snippet: A dispute over Liliane Bettencourt, 92, has riveted France by opening a window on the private lives of the rich and contested.
lead_paragraph: BORDEAUX, France — For five weeks, a French version of “Downton Abbey” has been unfolding in a courtroom here, providing a rare glimpse into the discreet lives of the ultrarich.

abstract: It can develop from insidious bleeding caused by an indirect trauma so trivial that a patient had long forgotten it.
snippet: It can develop from insidious bleeding caused by an indirect trauma so trivial that a patient had long forgotten it.
lead_paragraph: You don’t have to hit your head to develop an insidious bleed between the soft covering of your brain and the brain itself that in days, weeks or months can threaten your health or life.

abstract: Mr. Dickinson was an award-winning British mystery writer whose books for adults and children often crossed the boundaries between crime, adventure, science fiction, fantasy and suspense.
snippet: Mr. Dickinson was an award-winning British mystery writer whose books for adults and children often crossed the boundaries between crime, adventure, science fiction, fantasy and suspense.
lead_paragraph: Peter Dickinson, an award-winning British mystery writer whose books for adults and children often crossed the boundaries separating the genres of crime, adventure, science fiction, fantasy and suspense, died on Wednesday, his 88th birthday, in Winchester, Hampshire, England.

headline.main: Peter Dickinson, Author, Dies at 88; Master Plotter Relished a Good Puzzle
headline.print_headline: Peter Dickinson, Author, Dies at 88; Master Plotter Relished a Good Puzzle

abstract: The game continues to be haunted by far more vital issues than “Deflategate.”
snippet: The game continues to be haunted by far more vital issues than “Deflategate.”
lead_paragraph: “Deflategate” always sounded so childish: Did the star quarterback know that air had been secretly leaked from footballs he was throwing to help him win a big game? There’s still no firm answer to that question after an exhaustive court fight. But here comes the National Football League season nevertheless, and there is the star quarterback, Tom Brady, free to throw footballs again for the New England Patriots, having prevailed last week against an attempt by the league commissioner, Roger Goodell, to suspend him for four games.

snippet: Television highlights.
lead_paragraph: THE ROCKY HORROR PICTURE SHOW (1975) Hopped-up on Halloween candy? Take a jump to the left and then step to the right at this 40th-anniversary midnight streaming. Viewers are encouraged to dress as their favorite characters, throw rice at their iPads and then post live on Twitter from the safety of their own homes. It also comes with a free 30-day subscription to HBO’s streaming service. (HBO Now) (Image: Richard O’Brien as Riff Raff)

abstract: A friend-of-the-court brief says the settlement between the N.F.L. and retired players does not cover the full range of disorders linked to brain trauma.
snippet: A friend-of-the-court brief says the settlement between the N.F.L. and retired players does not cover the full range of disorders linked to brain trauma.
lead_paragraph: According to a friend-of-the-court brief filed Thursday, the settlement between the N.F.L. and the 5,000 retired players who accused the league of hiding the dangers of concussions is flawed because it does not cover the full range of physical and psychiatric disorders linked to brain trauma.

abstract: Paperback books of particular interest.
snippet: Paperback books of particular interest.
lead_paragraph: DYING EVERY DAY: Seneca at the Court of Nero,  by James Romm. (Vintage, $17.95.) Romm adeptly unravels the enigma of the great Stoic philosopher Seneca, who watched his student Nero spiral into madness as Roman emperor — a descent that saw family murders, the apocalyptic fire of A.D. 64 and a savage purging of the supreme minds of the Imperial Senate’s golden age.

abstract: Even a patient’s seemingly specific instructions for care can be less than direct, or unavailable when needed.
snippet: Even a patient’s seemingly specific instructions for care can be less than direct, or unavailable when needed.
lead_paragraph: The man had written an advance directive four years ago, before his advancing dementia had made communication difficult. He had been very specific.

abstract: The effects can be physical and psychological, professional and social. Yet many sufferers don’t realize it, or won’t admit it.
snippet: The effects can be physical and psychological, professional and social. Yet many sufferers don’t realize it, or won’t admit it.
lead_paragraph: Mark Hammel’s hearing was damaged in his 20s by machine gun fire when he served in the Israeli Army. But not until decades later, at 57, did he receive his first hearing aids.

headline.main: Hearing Loss Costs Far More Than Ability to Hear
headline.print_headline: Losing More Than the Ability to Hear

abstract: There had been three 911 calls in a little over three years about erratic behavior by Michael Juskin, who killed his wife, Rosalia, and then himself on Sunday.
snippet: There had been three 911 calls in a little over three years about erratic behavior by Michael Juskin, who killed his wife, Rosalia, and then himself on Sunday.
lead_paragraph: ELMWOOD PARK, N.J. — Three months ago, Rosalia Juskin dialed 911 from behind a locked basement door. She said her husband, Michael, 100, was ignoring her pleas, so she asked the police for help opening the door. When they arrived, Ms. Juskin, 88, described the episode as an accident.

abstract: Relatives of Duerson accused the movie of making up encounters that portrayed him as a villain, but the director said “Concussion” was “spiritually accurate.”
snippet: Relatives of Duerson accused the movie of making up encounters that portrayed him as a villain, but the director said “Concussion” was “spiritually accurate.”
lead_paragraph: In Will Smith’s new movie, “Concussion,” the former N.F.L. player Dave Duerson confronts the film’s protagonist, the pathologist Bennet Omalu, whose findings of chronic traumatic encephalopathy in pro football players shook the league. Duerson blocks the Nigerian-born Omalu from entering a medical conference, calls him a quack, and tells him to go back to Africa and to “get away from our game.”

abstract: Louise Penny, whose novel “The Nature of the Beast” is No. 3 on the hardcover fiction list, once said: “I know that if I’m not in the top five on the Times best-seller list, I’m going to feel like a failure.”
snippet: Louise Penny, whose novel “The Nature of the Beast” is No. 3 on the hardcover fiction list, once said: “I know that if I’m not in the top five on the Times best-seller list, I’m going to feel like a failure.”
lead_paragraph: The 11th Coming: “The Nature of the Beast,” Louise Penny’s 11th novel about the Québécois detective Armand Gamache, hits the hardcover fiction list at No. 3. Penny started the series in 2005 after two decades as a CBC radio host, and its popularity caught her by surprise. “It’s difficult to learn from success. I’ve learned more from my mistakes,” she told the author and critic Joel Yanofsky in 2013. “Fortunately, I’m capable of manufacturing my own problems.” In her 20s and early 30s those included a battle with alcoholism, and later a five-year bout of writer’s block that was, according to Yanofsky, “mainly spent watching Oprah, eating gummy bears and lying to everyone, including her husband, about how well her writing was going.” Things have improved since then. “Now I know that if I’m not in the top five on the Times best-seller list, I’m going to feel like a failure,” she said in the same interview. No worries here! But that doesn’t mean Penny’s life is challenge-free: In the past few years she’s had to care for her husband as he slides into dementia. “I find now that the writing is a safe harbor,” she told The Vancouver Sun last month. “It’s a place I go to that is mine.” You have to wonder if Penny had her husband’s condition in mind when she quoted Yeats’s “The Second Coming” in the new book — that’s the poem about things falling apart and the center not holding, which concludes, “And what rough beast, its hour come round at last, / Slouches towards Bethlehem to be born?” Maybe. But mostly, Penny told The Sun, “the beast is ourselves.”

abstract: “I Understand Everything Better,” starring David Neumann at Abrons Arts, suggests that everything in life can be understood by looking to nature.
snippet: “I Understand Everything Better,” starring David Neumann at Abrons Arts, suggests that everything in life can be understood by looking to nature.
lead_paragraph: Hurricane Sandy is a marker for the choreographer David Neumann, whose life around that time underwent serious turbulence. His mother died the summer before the hurricane, his father a few weeks after the storm. (Both were esteemed actors in the experimental theater company Mabou Mines.) Somewhere along the way, Mr. Neumann turned to a quote from Albert Einstein: “Look deep into nature and you will understand everything better.”

abstract: Most of us will face quandaries far more nuanced than those covered by end-of-life legislation.
snippet: Most of us will face quandaries far more nuanced than those covered by end-of-life legislation.
lead_paragraph: One co­ld March day, when she was 84 and suffering from congestive heart failure, my beautiful mother went to the garage and measured her Camry’s tailpipe, planning to buy a hose to fit it. She was grieving my father’s recent death, living alone in Connecticut with occasional visits from her three grown children in California, and suffering too much chest pain and breathlessness to weed her beloved garden. “There is a possibility for a timely escape,” she wrote in the journal I discovered after her death. “And I will take it.”

abstract: More people who are in bad, but not dire, financial situations are turning to sites like GoFundMe for help covering costs including medical care and tuition.
snippet: More people who are in bad, but not dire, financial situations are turning to sites like GoFundMe for help covering costs including medical care and tuition.
lead_paragraph: “I can’t even believe I’m writing this, or asking for this, but this is the reality.”

abstract: A salve when my father’s body and mind faltered.
snippet: A salve when my father’s body and mind faltered.
lead_paragraph: My father was a great walker. It was his only sport and his only pastime, if you don’t count reading or going to synagogue. He recalled walks the way some people recount epic ballgames, marathon strolls he accomplished as a young man when he and his friend Fred, a refugee like him, would wander from Washington Heights to Greenwich Village and back again.

headline.main: The Walking Cure
headline.print_headline: Walk No. 11: The Walking Cure

abstract: Starting its third and final season, this HBO series features Laurie Metcalf as a doctor in an extended-care unit for patients with serious disease or the infirmities of old age.
snippet: Starting its third and final season, this HBO series features Laurie Metcalf as a doctor in an extended-care unit for patients with serious disease or the infirmities of old age.
lead_paragraph: In the extended-care ward that is the setting for HBO’s series “Getting On,” some patients are entering the final phase of life. They’re generally sent off with a combination of dignity and abasement. That same seemingly contradictory combination will certainly mark the send-off for the series itself, which begins its third and final season on Sunday night.

headline.main: ‘Getting On,’ Played With Crudity and Grace
headline.print_headline: As the End Looms, Crudity and Grace (Like Always)

abstract: Mr. Channing combined careers as a venture capitalist, a sculptor in wood and a maker of well-regarded wines on the South Fork of Long Island, N.Y.
snippet: Mr. Channing combined careers as a venture capitalist, a sculptor in wood and a maker of well-regarded wines on the South Fork of Long Island, N.Y.
lead_paragraph: Walter Channing Jr., who combined careers as a venture capitalist, sculptor and well-regarded vintner on Long Island, died on March 12 in Southampton, N.Y. He was 74.

abstract: I loved my mother and my drinking, but both were limiting my potential.
snippet: I loved my mother and my drinking, but both were limiting my potential.
lead_paragraph: The last time I wished my mother dead, I meant it. I was on the plane home to New York City after visiting her in Beaumont, Tex., where she was in what I now know were the final stages of Lewy body dementia.

abstract: Poland has the highest levels in Europe of the tiny pollution particles that are strongly linked to serious health problems like heart attacks, strokes, cancer and even dementia.
snippet: Poland has the highest levels in Europe of the tiny pollution particles that are strongly linked to serious health problems like heart attacks, strokes, cancer and even dementia.
lead_paragraph: MYSLOWICE, Poland — The children Karolina Zolna knows huff and puff after a few minutes of exercise. Two years ago, her infant daughter spent four months in the hospital with pneumonia. The doctors did not identify a cause, but to Ms. Zolna, the reason for the baby’s illness was obvious.

abstract: Mrs. Newhouse was the longtime chairwoman of the Fresh Air Fund, which pays for poor children from New York City to go summer camp upstate or to stay with host families in rural and suburban areas.
snippet: Mrs. Newhouse was the longtime chairwoman of the Fresh Air Fund, which pays for poor children from New York City to go summer camp upstate or to stay with host families in rural and suburban areas.
lead_paragraph: Susan Newhouse, the longtime chairwoman of the Fresh Air Fund, among other philanthropic endeavors, and a fixture of New York high society, died on Thursday at her home in Manhattan. She was 80.

abstract: The changes are part of a further effort to improve nursing home ratings by raising the bar to achieving a high score in the quality measures area.
snippet: The changes are part of a further effort to improve nursing home ratings by raising the bar to achieving a high score in the quality measures area.
lead_paragraph: The federal government on Thursday announced that it was changing the way it measures nursing homes, essentially adjusting the curve that it uses to rate homes to make it more difficult for them to earn coveted four- and five-star government ratings.

abstract: Digital devices intended to transform elder care often fail, in part because tech entrepreneurs don’t fully understand the task or the consumers.
snippet: Digital devices intended to transform elder care often fail, in part because tech entrepreneurs don’t fully understand the task or the consumers.
lead_paragraph: Daily, breathless announcements arrive in my inbox, heralding technology products for older adults.

abstract: The film “Still Alice” focuses attention on a disease that can devastate families emotionally and financially.
snippet: The film “Still Alice” focuses attention on a disease that can devastate families emotionally and financially.
lead_paragraph: MIDWAY through the film “Still Alice,” which tracks the growing grip of Alzheimer’s on a 50-something Columbia University professor, that professor, played by Julianne Moore, stands at a lectern to address an Alzheimer’s conference. She is holding a yellow highlighter and a copy of her speech.

headline.main: In Alzheimer’s Cases, Financial Ruin and Abuse Are Always Lurking
headline.print_headline: In Alzheimer’s Cases, Financial Ruin and Abuse Are Always Lurking

abstract: Family members caring for older adults struggle to balance work demands, yet paid leave is mandatory in just three states. That may be changing.
snippet: Family members caring for older adults struggle to balance work demands, yet paid leave is mandatory in just three states. That may be changing.
lead_paragraph: Her supervisors empathized. They knew why Marcy Sherman-Lewis, a customer service agent, was missing workdays: Both her parents, who lived an hour away, had Alzheimer’s disease.

abstract: Fullmer, who reigned when fight clubs abounded and Friday night fights were a television staple, was known for his title bouts with Sugar Ray Robinson and Carmen Basilio.
snippet: Fullmer, who reigned when fight clubs abounded and Friday night fights were a television staple, was known for his title bouts with Sugar Ray Robinson and Carmen Basilio.
lead_paragraph: Gene Fullmer, the middleweight boxing champion known for a brawling style and an ability to shake off punches and remembered for his title fights with Sugar Ray Robinson and Carmen Basilio, died on Monday in Taylorsville, Utah. He was 83.

abstract: Kado, in the city’s Kreuzberg neighborhood, stocks versions of the sweet imported from 10 countries.
snippet: Kado, in the city’s Kreuzberg neighborhood, stocks versions of the sweet imported from 10 countries.
lead_paragraph: “I went from marketing to the markets themselves and let’s just say people were a bit surprised,” says Ilse Böge. In 1996, she gave up her job as a financial consultant in Berlin to start hawking something very different: licorice. “The first bank I went to for a loan pretty firmly suggested I sell children’s clothes, nuts, chocolates, basically anything in addition to licorice, but I wanted to specialize,” she says.

abstract: The singer began her career in the 1940s on radio in Ohio and then became a regular on the NBC music variety show “Midwestern Hayride.”
snippet: The singer began her career in the 1940s on radio in Ohio and then became a regular on the NBC music variety show “Midwestern Hayride.”
lead_paragraph: Bonnie Lou, a singer who achieved national stardom in the 1950s by recording country and rockabilly hits and performing on television and radio, but whose career declined after she turned down a major-label deal, died on Tuesday in Cheviot, Ohio. She was 91.

headline.print_headline: Bonnie Lou, 91, Country Singing Star

abstract: Gagne wrestled professionally from the late 1940s until the 1980s and was a transitional figure between the early 20th century barnstormers and the steroidal sideshows of today.
snippet: Gagne wrestled professionally from the late 1940s until the 1980s and was a transitional figure between the early 20th century barnstormers and the steroidal sideshows of today.
lead_paragraph: Eighth Avenue traffic was disorganized, pedestrian traffic was jammed for blocks north and south, side doors at Madison Square Garden were torn from their hinges as the crowd stormed the entrances. It was the largest crowd at the Garden in 25 years — larger than for championship fights, rodeos, tennis matches or the circus.

abstract: Dr. Sokoloff won the Albert Lasker Clinical Medical Research Award in 1981 for his role in developing the vivid color images that map brain function.
snippet: Dr. Sokoloff won the Albert Lasker Clinical Medical Research Award in 1981 for his role in developing the vivid color images that map brain function.
lead_paragraph: Dr. Louis Sokoloff, who pioneered the PET scan technique for measuring human brain function and diagnosing disorders, died on July 30 in Washington. He was 93.

abstract: Television highlights.
snippet: Television highlights.
lead_paragraph: 4:30 P.M. (E!) MAGIC MIKE (2012) In a role inspired by his stint as a stripper in Florida, Channing Tatum stars as the gyrating main attraction at Xquisite, in what Manohla Dargis, writing in The New York Times, called “Steven Soderbergh’s funny, enjoyable romp about male strippers and the American dream.” Alex Pettyfer is Adam, a college dropout who is pushed onstage. At first he’s resistant. Then Madonna’s “Like a Virgin” begins to throb. “The collaboration between Mr. Soderbergh and the relatively untested Mr. Tatum is itself a gamble, one that has brought out the best in each,” Ms. Dargis said.

abstract: Television highlights.
snippet: Television highlights.
lead_paragraph: 8 P.M. (Smithsonian) LINCOLN’S LAST DAY Commemorating the 150th anniversary of the assassination of President Abraham Lincoln by John Wilkes Booth, this documentary uses computer-generated maps of 1865 Washington and artifacts from the Smithsonian’s National Museum of American History and from Ford’s Theater — among them, Lincoln’s gold watch and hat, and Booth’s diary and derringer — to piece together the movements of key players in the plot to avenge the defeated South after the Civil War and throw the future of the Union into question. In “Living With Lincoln,” at 9 on HBO, Peter Kunhardt chronicles his family’s efforts to assemble and care for one of the largest private collections of 19th-century American photography, most of it devoted to Lincoln, across five generations. The Meserve-Kunhardt Collection — more than 73,000 items, including 57,000 prints and thousands of books, among other things — was bought by the Beinecke Rare Book & Manuscript Library at Yale last month.

abstract: When I bought my first New York apartment, the down payment came from my grandfather, who had long offered support and financial advice.
snippet: When I bought my first New York apartment, the down payment came from my grandfather, who had long offered support and financial advice.
lead_paragraph: I’ll admit it now: All those Y2K predictions had me scared about what would befall the world when 1999 became 2000.

abstract: Television highlights.
snippet: Television highlights.
lead_paragraph: 11:05 A.M. (Cinemax) TRANSAMERICA (2005) Felicity Huffman goes full-frontal as Bree, who, though still technically a man, passes for a woman with tasteful pink outfits, meticulous makeup and a breathy voice. But before gender reassignment surgery, she needs to tie up a loose end — so she hits the road with the son (Kevin Zegers) she never knew she had. Duncan Tucker’s debut feature “sets out to affirm Bree’s dignity, to liberate her and others like her from any association with camp or freakishness,” A. O. Scott wrote in The New York Times. “That the film succeeds without slipping too far into sentimentality or didacticism is in no small measure the result of Ms. Huffman’s wit and grace.” (Image: Ms. Huffman)

abstract: While any dress, even a handmade one, is a product, couture collections reflect a special view of reality.
snippet: While any dress, even a handmade one, is a product, couture collections reflect a special view of reality.
lead_paragraph: PARIS — There are shows and then there are shows. As couture ran its course in Paris, the chatter runway-side had turned to another spectacle taking place in Bordeaux: the trial of 10 people accused of defrauding Liliane Bettencourt, the 92-year-old L’Oréal heiress and richest woman in France. Well, when you are whiling away the minutes pre-show, it helps to plug into the local gossip. Think of it as parallel views onto lifestyles of the affluent and almost famous.

abstract: Ms. Moody’s memoir powerfully described growing up black in the Jim Crow era and taking part in the civil rights movement as a young woman.
snippet: Ms. Moody’s memoir powerfully described growing up black in the Jim Crow era and taking part in the civil rights movement as a young woman.
lead_paragraph: Anne Moody, whose searing memoir, “Coming of Age in Mississippi,” told what it was like to grow up black in the era of Jim Crow, died on Feb. 5 at her home in Gloster, Miss. She was 74.

abstract: There should be a legal age for high-impact contact sports.
snippet: There should be a legal age for high-impact contact sports.
lead_paragraph: Sacramento — WE’VE known since 1964 that cigarette smoking is harmful to your health. We’ve known for more than 40 years that alcohol damages the developing brain of a child. We’ve known since the mid-70s that asbestos causes cancer and other serious diseases. Knowing what we know now, we do not smoke in enclosed public spaces like airplanes; we have passed laws to keep children from smoking or drinking alcohol; and we do not use asbestos as an industrial product.

abstract: In this film written by Alan Bennett, based on his play, Ms. Smith plays a character opposite in many ways, except one, from her “Downton Abbey” character.
snippet: In this film written by Alan Bennett, based on his play, Ms. Smith plays a character opposite in many ways, except one, from her “Downton Abbey” character.
lead_paragraph: Those eyes. They’ve seen it all and taken its measure. And woe be to someone or something that displeases the critical spectator.

abstract: Mr. Blatt was one of the few survivors of a rare revolt and mass escape from a Nazi death camp in occupied Poland in October 1943, during World War II.
snippet: Mr. Blatt was one of the few survivors of a rare revolt and mass escape from a Nazi death camp in occupied Poland in October 1943, during World War II.
lead_paragraph: Thomas Blatt, one of the few survivors of a rare revolt and mass escape from a Nazi death camp in occupied Poland during World War II, died on Saturday at his home in Santa Barbara, Calif. He was 88.

abstract: Mr. Lewis, 89, joked about old age as he reflected on his career at this club, where he has performed for over a half-century.
snippet: Mr. Lewis, 89, joked about old age as he reflected on his career at this club, where he has performed for over a half-century.
lead_paragraph: “Thank you for coming, and what do you want?” Jerry Lewis said with mock impatience, addressing the 200 or so members and guests of the Friars Club who had come to see him on Monday night.

abstract: Mr. Sheets participated for more than 40 years in the Special Olympics, going back to its first international summer games at Chicago’s Soldier Field in 1968.
snippet: Mr. Sheets participated for more than 40 years in the Special Olympics, going back to its first international summer games at Chicago’s Soldier Field in 1968.
lead_paragraph: Martin Sheets, who became a face of the Special Olympics, winning more than 250 medals competing for more than 40 years in its events for people with intellectual disabilities, died on Thursday in Greensboro, N.C. He was 62.

abstract: Ms. Sivard drew attention to the disparity between social and military spending for more than three decades.
snippet: Ms. Sivard drew attention to the disparity between social and military spending for more than three decades.
lead_paragraph: Ruth Sivard, an economist who for more than three decades drew attention to the disparity between social and military spending around the globe, even after the Pentagon objected to her making that comparison for a federal agency, died on Aug. 21 at her home in Washington. She was 99.

abstract: Montador, who died in February at age 35, is the fifth known former N.H.L. player to have had C.T.E., the disease associated with repeated hits to the head.
snippet: Montador, who died in February at age 35, is the fifth known former N.H.L. player to have had C.T.E., the disease associated with repeated hits to the head.
lead_paragraph: The brain of Steve Montador, a former N.H.L. player who died in February at age 35, was found to have widespread chronic traumatic encephalopathy, or C.T.E., a disease associated with repeated hits to the head.

abstract: A new Showtime film about Smith, who led North Carolina’s basketball program and died last month, presents a uniformly positive view of a major figure in college sports history.
snippet: A new Showtime film about Smith, who led North Carolina’s basketball program and died last month, presents a uniformly positive view of a major figure in college sports history.
lead_paragraph: “Dean Smith,” the new documentary about the North Carolina basketball coach, is purely a homage. The portrait is not of a difficult or meanspirited man but of one whom any recruit’s parents would want to have in their home: polite, old-fashioned, supportive, averse to cursing (but not occasional sarcasm), hypercompetitive, humble, colorblind and pro-education (really).

abstract: Can Alzheimer’s ever have an upside?
snippet: Can Alzheimer’s ever have an upside?
lead_paragraph: DENVER — “CAN you make sure it has lots of stuff?” my mom regularly asked the server at her favorite Italian restaurant. Apparently, the minestrone soup was mostly broth with just a couple of noodles, which was unacceptable. “Really scoop it up,” she instructed, adding her nervous, friendly laugh. With her salmon, she demanded all sauces on the side, and an additional plate of lemon slices. Sometimes she brought her own dessert from the place she liked down the street. Her fastidiousness made me want to shrink into the jar of Parmesan cheese, but what could I do? That was my mom.

headline.main: My Mother, Lost and Found
headline.print_headline: My Mother, Lost and Found

abstract: When Sandy Bem found out she had Alzheimer’s, she resolved that before the disease stole her mind, she would kill herself. The question was, when?
snippet: When Sandy Bem found out she had Alzheimer’s, she resolved that before the disease stole her mind, she would kill herself. The question was, when?
lead_paragraph: Sandy Bem, a Cornell psychology professor one month shy of her 65th birthday, was alone in her bedroom one night in May 2009, watching an HBO documentary called “The Alzheimer’s Project.” For two years, she had been experiencing what she called “cognitive oddities”: forgetting the names of things or confusing words that sounded similar. She once complained about a “blizzard” on her foot, when she meant a blister; she brought home a bag of plums and, standing in her kitchen, pulled one out and said to a friend: “Is this a plum? I can’t quite seem to fully know.”

abstract: Google’s Sidewalk Labs will pursue technologies to cut pollution, curb energy use, streamline transportation and reduce the cost of city living.
snippet: Google’s Sidewalk Labs will pursue technologies to cut pollution, curb energy use, streamline transportation and reduce the cost of city living.
lead_paragraph: Google’s ambitions and investments have increasingly broadened beyond its digital origins in Internet search and online advertising into the arena of physical objects: self-driving cars, Internet-connected eyeglasses, smart thermostats and a biotech venture to develop life-extending treatments.

abstract: Al Pacino plays a revered stage and screen actor who fears he is losing his mojo in “The Humbling.”
snippet: Al Pacino plays a revered stage and screen actor who fears he is losing his mojo in “The Humbling.”
lead_paragraph: In his later fiction, Philip Roth has addressed the indignities of aging with a squirm-inducing candor. How many readers (or filmgoers) are eager to contemplate the loss of their powers until it is staring them in the face?

abstract: Just as standardized tests are driving education, medical tests are dominating decisions on how best to care for patients.
snippet: Just as standardized tests are driving education, medical tests are dominating decisions on how best to care for patients.
lead_paragraph: I spent the usual long afternoon at work doing little but ordering tests, far more than I honestly thought any patient needed, but that’s what we do these days. Guidelines mandate tests, and patients expect them; abnormal tests mean medication, and medication means more tests.

abstract: Solanezumab, from Eli Lilly, is getting another look for mild cases, and Biogen said data from a small group taking aducanumab showed mixed results.
snippet: Solanezumab, from Eli Lilly, is getting another look for mild cases, and Biogen said data from a small group taking aducanumab showed mixed results.
lead_paragraph: New data released on Wednesday raised hopes somewhat that an experimental Alzheimer’s drug from Eli Lilly & Company might be effective. At the same time, other results were released on Wednesday that could reduce expectations a bit for a similar drug being developed by Biogen.

abstract: Mr. Featherstone’s first pink plastic flamingo came off the assembly line in 1957.
snippet: Mr. Featherstone’s first pink plastic flamingo came off the assembly line in 1957.
lead_paragraph: Don Featherstone did not invent Phoenicopterus ruber: Nature took care of that eons ago. But what Mr. Featherstone did nearly six decades ago — in the process indelibly altering the landscape of midcentury America — was to cast the creature in plastic and attach slender, rodlike legs for planting it in the ground.

abstract: We’ve failed the mentally ill and the mentally disabled.
snippet: We’ve failed the mentally ill and the mentally disabled.
lead_paragraph: LAST month, three ethicists from the University of Pennsylvania argued in the Journal of the American Medical Association that the movement to deinstitutionalize the mentally ill has been a failure. Deinstitutionalization, they wrote, has in truth been “transinstitutionalization.” As a hospital psychiatrist, I see this every day. Patients with chronic, severe mental illnesses are still in facilities — only now they are in medical hospitals, nursing homes and, increasingly, jails and prisons, places that are less appropriate and more expensive than long-term psychiatric institutions.

abstract: Some signs that you may be having a heart attack, and what you should do.
snippet: Some signs that you may be having a heart attack, and what you should do.
lead_paragraph: Tremendous progress has been made in treating heart disease, but it is still the biggest killer of Americans, accounting for one in seven deaths. Here are answers to some common questions about the symptoms and treatment of heart attacks and narrowed aortic valves.

abstract: The company, which bought an unproven Alzheimer’s drug for $5 million, is now valued at nearly $3 billion. The successful debut renews concerns that biotechnology stocks are in bubble territory.
snippet: The company, which bought an unproven Alzheimer’s drug for $5 million, is now valued at nearly $3 billion. The successful debut renews concerns that biotechnology stocks are in bubble territory.
lead_paragraph: A 29-year-old former hedge fund manager has pulled off what is perhaps the largest initial public stock offering ever in the biotechnology industry, creating a company with a market value approaching $3 billion on the basis of an unproved drug for Alzheimer’s disease that it acquired for $5 million.

abstract: If doctors visited patients at home, the benefit to the health care system would be enormous.
snippet: If doctors visited patients at home, the benefit to the health care system would be enormous.
lead_paragraph: A FEW weeks ago, in the hospital where I work, I was telling a 92-year-old patient about her discharge plan. I wanted her to follow up in my office in a week. Frail and soft-spoken, she asked me if instead I could visit her at home. “I’m afraid not,” I said automatically, but when she asked me why, I didn’t have a good answer.

abstract: Mr. Marshall was serving a life sentence in the 1984 contract murder of his wife, a case that became the subject of Joe McGinniss’s book “Blind Faith.”
snippet: Mr. Marshall was serving a life sentence in the 1984 contract murder of his wife, a case that became the subject of Joe McGinniss’s book “Blind Faith.”
lead_paragraph: Robert O. Marshall, a life insurance salesman whose conviction and almost 30-year imprisonment for the contract killing of his wife inspired the Joe McGinniss book “Blind Faith” and a television movie of the same name, died in prison on Saturday in Bridgeton, N.J., while awaiting a parole hearing. He was 75.

abstract: Ms. Arden, whose exuberance as a publisher invigorated the book industry, promoted countless best sellers, including “Mommie Dearest” and “The Peter Principle.”
snippet: Ms. Arden, whose exuberance as a publisher invigorated the book industry, promoted countless best sellers, including “Mommie Dearest” and “The Peter Principle.”
lead_paragraph: Sherry Arden, whose exuberance as a promoter and perspicacity as a publisher helped invigorate the book industry with a raft of celebrity tell-all memoirs like Christina Crawford’s “Mommie Dearest” and pop psychology primers like Gail Sheehy’s “Pathfinders,” died on Jan. 27 at her home in Santa Monica, Calif. She was 91.

abstract: Ms. Sonnabend had a long and successful collaboration with the British choreographer and Royal Ballet director Kenneth MacMillan.
snippet: Ms. Sonnabend had a long and successful collaboration with the British choreographer and Royal Ballet director Kenneth MacMillan.
lead_paragraph: LONDON — Yolanda Sonnabend, a theater designer and painter who had a strong influence on the work of the British choreographer and Royal Ballet director Kenneth MacMillan, died on Nov. 9 in London. She was 80.

abstract: A Facebook post drew 150 people to a Jerusalem hilltop for a funeral that family members feared might not have a minyan, the quorum of 10 required for the Jewish mourning prayer.
snippet: A Facebook post drew 150 people to a Jerusalem hilltop for a funeral that family members feared might not have a minyan, the quorum of 10 required for the Jewish mourning prayer.
lead_paragraph: JERUSALEM — Most of the mourners had never met Nate Remer, who survived the Holocaust hiding in a Ukrainian forest, built a successful wholesale hardware business in Southern California and had severe dementia for 15 years before dying Tuesday at 82. They did not know his son, Gary, a professor at Tulane University, or his grandson, Moshe Alexander, who moved to Israel five years ago and works in high tech.

headline.print_headline: Helping to Mourn a Holocaust Survivor

abstract: I would promise to skip expensive, risky interventions in exchange for better daily care.
snippet: I would promise to skip expensive, risky interventions in exchange for better daily care.
lead_paragraph: I spent the last Sunday of my father’s life sitting by his bed on the hospice unit in a small Connecticut hospital. He was dying of pneumonia, once called “the old man’s friend.” There was a nondenominational chapel down the hall, and a sheet cake in the kitchen. His hand was warm. Reassured by the quiet presence of the hospice nurses and feeling the mysterious quickening of life through his veins, I gave over to being his daughter and letting him be my father one last time.

headline.main: Imagine a Medicare ‘Part Q’ for Quality at the End of Life

abstract: Colon cancer patients who were heavy coffee drinkers had a far lower risk of dying or having their cancer return than those who did not drink coffee.
snippet: Colon cancer patients who were heavy coffee drinkers had a far lower risk of dying or having their cancer return than those who did not drink coffee.
lead_paragraph: Colon cancer patients who were heavy coffee drinkers had a far lower risk of dying or having their cancer return than those who did not drink coffee, with significant benefits starting at two to three cups a day, a new study found. Patients who drank four cups of caffeinated coffee or more a day had half the rate of recurrence or death than noncoffee drinkers.

abstract: In her latest work, Patricia Marx sets out to uncover why her brain, clogged with too many bits of information, does not seem to work the way it once did.
snippet: In her latest work, Patricia Marx sets out to uncover why her brain, clogged with too many bits of information, does not seem to work the way it once did.
lead_paragraph: When you need something short and funny to read, it helps to have a few old journalistic favorites on standby. Mine include Dave Barry’s seminal Miami Herald piece “Can New York Save Itself?” and a Guardian article from 2002 in which the writer, Tim Dowling, was forced by his editors to spend a night in a trench in his backyard.

headline.main: Review: ‘Let’s Be Less Stupid,’ a Distracted Meditation on Absent-Mindedness
headline.print_headline: A Distracted Meditation on Absent-Mindedness

abstract: Cy Twombly’s last paintings celebrate his lifelong interest in flowers, Greek mythology, ships and the sea, and lines of enigmatic writing.
snippet: Cy Twombly’s last paintings celebrate his lifelong interest in flowers, Greek mythology, ships and the sea, and lines of enigmatic writing.
lead_paragraph: Painters in their old age present an interesting spectrum. André Derain and Giorgio de Chirico, who had been so shocking, drifted off after World War I in a conservative, neoclassical direction (De Chirico even faked his trademark earlier metaphysical paintings from time to time). Titian did some of his greatest work into his 80s; Jasper Johns continues to hold his own as a master. De Kooning painted despite dementia, with contested results.

abstract: Readers solve the case of a middle-aged woman with arthritis who developed a wasting illness after what looked like a simple cold.
snippet: Readers solve the case of a middle-aged woman with arthritis who developed a wasting illness after what looked like a simple cold.
lead_paragraph: On Thursday we challenged Well readers to solve the case of a middle-aged woman with arthritis who developed a wasting illness after what looked like a simple cold. Her rheumatologist was worried that the immune suppressing medications the patient took to treat her joint disease had caused the new illness. More than 300 of you took on the challenge, and 17 of you correctly identified this rarity. The correct diagnosis is …

abstract: Ms. Elliot inspired generations of evangelical Christians by returning to preach the Gospel to the Indian tribe that had killed her husband.
snippet: Ms. Elliot inspired generations of evangelical Christians by returning to preach the Gospel to the Indian tribe that had killed her husband.
lead_paragraph: Elisabeth Elliot, a missionary who inspired generations of evangelical Christians by returning to Ecuador with her toddler daughter to preach the Gospel to the Indian tribe that had killed her husband, died on Monday at her home in Gloucester, Mass. She was 88.

headline.main: Elisabeth Elliot, Tenacious Missionary in Face of Tragedy, Dies at 88
headline.print_headline: Elisabeth Elliot, 88, Tenacious Missionary to Ecuador

abstract: He thought it was wrong to treat infections in terminally ill patients, until it was his turn.
snippet: He thought it was wrong to treat infections in terminally ill patients, until it was his turn.
lead_paragraph: When it came to offering medical interventions to severely ill patients with no hope of recovery, my father had a fiercely strong opinion: They were inappropriate. For decades as an infectious diseases specialist, he had been asked to treat infections in dying patients. Whenever possible, he said no.

headline.main: Overruling My Father

abstract: Learning what makes so-called von Economo neurons special could help point researchers to treatments for some kinds of mental decline.
snippet: Learning what makes so-called von Economo neurons special could help point researchers to treatments for some kinds of mental decline.
lead_paragraph: In 2010, a graduate student named Tamar Gefen got to know a remarkable group of older people.

headline.main: Studying Oversize Brain Cells for Links to Exceptional Memory

abstract: Neuroscientists have struggled to understand exactly how the mind’s cycles affect us. Studies of donated brains provide some answers.
snippet: Neuroscientists have struggled to understand exactly how the mind’s cycles affect us. Studies of donated brains provide some answers.
lead_paragraph: Throughout the day, a clock ticks inside our bodies. It rouses us in the morning and makes us sleepy at night. It raises and lowers our body temperature at the right times, and regulates the production of insulin and other hormones.

abstract: The finding, which can only be confirmed posthumously, was announced by Gifford’s family on Wednesday, more than three months after Gifford died at age 84.
snippet: The finding, which can only be confirmed posthumously, was announced by Gifford’s family on Wednesday, more than three months after Gifford died at age 84.
lead_paragraph: Frank Gifford, a Hall of Fame running back who was involved in one of the most brutal collisions in the N.F.L.’s history, was found to have had chronic traumatic encephalopathy, a degenerative brain disease.

abstract: Laura Lippman’s scrappy Baltimore private eye, Tess Monaghan, is back on the job in “Hush Hush.”
snippet: Laura Lippman’s scrappy Baltimore private eye, Tess Monaghan, is back on the job in “Hush Hush.”
lead_paragraph: Those daring adventures into the treacherous territory of the stand-alone novel are all very exciting, but readers do remain devoted to their series sleuths. So it’s good to see Laura Lippman’s scrappy Baltimore private eye, Tess Monaghan, back on the job in HUSH HUSH (Morrow/Harper­Collins, $26.99), a tough-minded but wonderfully entertaining book that might be called a parenting mystery. During the years she’s been out of commission, Tess has become the mother of a little girl, Carla Scout, now 3 years old and a real handful. (A first-class meltdown in the liquor aisle of a grocery store should endear the child to amused strangers, while piling up sympathy points for her mother.)

abstract: By giving Sydney Seau an abbreviated forum to speak on behalf of her father, the Pro Football Hall of Fame showed the folly of an exclusionary policy for dead inductees.
snippet: By giving Sydney Seau an abbreviated forum to speak on behalf of her father, the Pro Football Hall of Fame showed the folly of an exclusionary policy for dead inductees.
lead_paragraph: When Sydney Seau spoke briefly Saturday at the Pro Football Hall of Fame induction for her late father, Junior, she proved emphatically that the relatives of deceased inductees deserved to deliver full speeches at their enshrinement ceremonies. Who would have thought otherwise?

abstract: The allegations by the family of Mr. Marshall, who spent a few days at Rikers Island before transferring to an upstate prison in 2013, were made public in court filings this week.
snippet: The allegations by the family of Mr. Marshall, who spent a few days at Rikers Island before transferring to an upstate prison in 2013, were made public in court filings this week.
lead_paragraph: Anthony D. Marshall spent only a few days at Rikers Island in 2013 before being transferred to an upstate prison to serve his sentence for stealing tens of millions of dollars from his mother, the philanthropist and socialite Brooke Astor.

headline.main: Your Wednesday Briefing

abstract: Once the undisputed light-heavyweight titleholder, Johnson spent much of his career in the shadow of his bitter rival, Archie Moore.
snippet: Once the undisputed light-heavyweight titleholder, Johnson spent much of his career in the shadow of his bitter rival, Archie Moore.
lead_paragraph: Harold Johnson, a boxer who spent a year as the undisputed world light-heavyweight champion but who more often fought in the shadow of hard luck, getting the short end of a rivalry with Archie Moore and losing his title in an upset, died on Thursday in Philadelphia. He was 87.

abstract: Marvin Wexler, a commercial litigator, also cultivates another side of himself, reading poetry to a room full of elderly and disabled residents at a nursing home.
snippet: Marvin Wexler, a commercial litigator, also cultivates another side of himself, reading poetry to a room full of elderly and disabled residents at a nursing home.
lead_paragraph: On the public stage, Marvin Wexler is a hard-boiled commercial litigator, skilled at defending the unpopular: the actress Vanessa Redgrave, for instance, when she was cut from a role for supporting the Palestine Liberation Organization in the 1980s; more recently a New York City hospital, against accusations that it pressed Huguette Clark, the copper heiress and a longtime patient, to donate lavishly from her fortune.

abstract: Dr. White, a meteorologist, was the first person to lead the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration and warned of climate change long before it was widely recognized.
snippet: Dr. White, a meteorologist, was the first person to lead the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration and warned of climate change long before it was widely recognized.
lead_paragraph: Robert M. White, a meteorologist who revolutionized the nation’s weather forecasting system, was the first to lead the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration and warned of climate change long before it was widely recognized, died on Oct. 14 at his home in Chevy Chase, Md. He was 92.

abstract: On his mind are the past fortunes of Mitt Romney and George W. Bush when they hit New Hampshire, and Hillary Rodham Clinton’s approach in this key state
snippet: On his mind are the past fortunes of Mitt Romney and George W. Bush when they hit New Hampshire, and Hillary Rodham Clinton’s approach in this key state
lead_paragraph: BEDFORD, N.H. — His S.U.V.’s motor was running and an open door beckoned. But Jeb Bush, quite possibly the most media-friendly hopeful in the Republican presidential field, was not done answering questions.

abstract: Herbal supplements, brain-training games and puzzles are being tossed out as ways to fight cognitive decline, without much evidence that they work.
snippet: Herbal supplements, brain-training games and puzzles are being tossed out as ways to fight cognitive decline, without much evidence that they work.
lead_paragraph: With people worldwide living longer, marketers are seizing on every opportunity to sell remedies and devices that they claim can enhance memory and other cognitive functions and perhaps stave off dementia as people age.
