headline.main: For an Aging Brain, Looking for Ways to Keep Memory Sharp

abstract: Before making an advance directive, talk with your doctor and your caregiver about just how far end-of-life care should go at the cost of comfort.
snippet: Before making an advance directive, talk with your doctor and your caregiver about just how far end-of-life care should go at the cost of comfort.
lead_paragraph: Virgie Divinigracia had the kind of death last month that most Americans say they want: at home, relieved of physical and mental pain, surrounded by those she loved, “a beautiful death” as those present described it. Alas, this is true for too few Americans. Most still die in costly medical facilities tethered to machines, often unable to communicate, in a futile attempt to prolong their lives.

headline.main: Your Wednesday Briefing

abstract: The correspondence between these two authors gives us the feel of love rising off the page.
snippet: The correspondence between these two authors gives us the feel of love rising off the page.
lead_paragraph: If there’s anything left to be said about Eudora Welty, let it be this: She could make even home renovation sound remarkable.

abstract: Ms. Ring was a sounding board for Fitzgerald and after his death was a longtime source of information for biographers, filmmakers and fans.
snippet: Ms. Ring was a sounding board for Fitzgerald and after his death was a longtime source of information for biographers, filmmakers and fans.
lead_paragraph: Frances Kroll Ring, the personal secretary to F. Scott Fitzgerald for the last 20 months of his life and a longtime source of information for biographers, documentary filmmakers, students and fans, died on Thursday at her home in Los Angeles. She was 99.

abstract: Father Lo Schiavo, who spent 14 years as president of the University of San Francisco, made headlines when he suspended the men’s basketball program after repeated violations of N.C.A.A. rules.
snippet: Father Lo Schiavo, who spent 14 years as president of the University of San Francisco, made headlines when he suspended the men’s basketball program after repeated violations of N.C.A.A. rules.
lead_paragraph: The Rev. John Lo Schiavo, who spent 14 years as president of the University of San Francisco, notably making headlines when he took the rare step of suspending the men’s basketball program after repeated violations of National Collegiate Athletic Association rules, died on Friday in Los Gatos, Calif. He was 90.

abstract: When I came upon an ice bucket like hers, I didn’t even bargain.
snippet: When I came upon an ice bucket like hers, I didn’t even bargain.
lead_paragraph: ST. PETERSBURG, FLA. — My mother sat next to me on her sofa. She held a brass candlestick like a baton. “Put stickers on the things you’d like to have,” she said. “With your initials. So when I’m gone there’s no confusion.”

headline.main: Shopping for Antiques, Finding My Mother

abstract: Intimate struggles — autism, depression, cancer — were significant themes among the theater offerings at this festival.
snippet: Intimate struggles — autism, depression, cancer — were significant themes among the theater offerings at this festival.
lead_paragraph: EDINBURGH — Despite loathing audience participation, there I stood onstage in a small black box performance space here recently, gyrating my hips and spinning a hula hoop before a packed house. Nearby, a couple of people were clumsily attempting to spin plates on sticks, and others in the audience were trying the same with anything suitable they could find in pockets or handbags.

headline.print_headline: Personal Stories Move Front and Center

abstract: The available evidence shows it helps with pain and other problems, but obstacles to research are slowing further insights.
snippet: The available evidence shows it helps with pain and other problems, but obstacles to research are slowing further insights.
lead_paragraph: It is becoming easier to get marijuana, legally. In the last 20 years or so, 23 states, as well as the District of Columbia, have passed laws that make it legal to use marijuana for medical treatments. So have some countries, like Austria, Canada, Finland, Germany, Israel and Spain.

abstract: “Love the Coopers” adds to the brief collection of films that delve into Christmas discontents.
snippet: “Love the Coopers” adds to the brief collection of films that delve into Christmas discontents.
lead_paragraph: “Love the Coopers,” a new holiday film directed by Jessie Nelson and starring Diane Keaton and John Goodman as Charlotte and Sam, a couple of ex-hippies who find themselves with a large Pittsburgh family after four decades of marriage, provides all the time-honored trimmings of classic seasonal fare. There’s warm, wintry music, snowy hills full of sledders and boarders, wrapped gifts and glittering evergreens.

abstract: Mamie Gummer plays a veteran of combat in Afghanistan adjusting to life at home and the pain of her injuries, both physiological and psychological.
snippet: Mamie Gummer plays a veteran of combat in Afghanistan adjusting to life at home and the pain of her injuries, both physiological and psychological.
lead_paragraph: It takes a brave playwright to saddle her work with the less than enticing title “Ugly Lies the Bone.” The play itself, about a severely wounded war veteran attempting to put together a new life, confirms that Lindsey Ferrentino is a writer of dauntless conviction. This bracing drama from the Roundabout Underground program, starring a superb Mamie Gummer as that damaged vet, confronts an achingly topical issue with hardheaded honesty and admirable compassion.

abstract: Sydney Seau paid tribute to her father, Junior, in an onstage interview after the showing of a video, but the Hall of Fame did not address the circumstances of his death.
snippet: Sydney Seau paid tribute to her father, Junior, in an onstage interview after the showing of a video, but the Hall of Fame did not address the circumstances of his death.
lead_paragraph: CANTON, Ohio — At a dinner and ceremony Thursday night as part of the Pro Football Hall of Fame induction weekend, Sydney Seau received a standing ovation after Roger Goodell, the N.F.L. commissioner, presented her with a gift honoring her father, Junior, one of the game’s most celebrated linebackers.

abstract: The Defense Department is consolidating some of the small counseling programs created to stem a rise in suicides during the wars in Iraq and Afghanistan.
snippet: The Defense Department is consolidating some of the small counseling programs created to stem a rise in suicides during the wars in Iraq and Afghanistan.
lead_paragraph: PISCATAWAY, N.J. — In a row of beige cubicles in a suburban office park, a hulking former Army sergeant hunched over his phone next to a photo taken in Afghanistan, a few days before he was hurt by a roadside bomb.

abstract: The wrongful-death suit, filed in Wisconsin, accuses the youth football league of failing to warn players about, and protect them from, the dangers of head trauma.
snippet: The wrongful-death suit, filed in Wisconsin, accuses the youth football league of failing to warn players about, and protect them from, the dangers of head trauma.
lead_paragraph: The family of a football player who committed suicide and was later found to have chronic traumatic encephalopathy, a degenerative brain disease, has sued the youth league Pop Warner, claiming that it failed to warn players about, and protect them from, the dangers of head trauma.

abstract: A young orphan and a widow run a charity scam amid the corruption of World War II London.
snippet: A young orphan and a widow run a charity scam amid the corruption of World War II London.
lead_paragraph: Show of hands: Was anybody here an odd-looking, precocious, misunderstood child? Oh. . . . Everybody? Maybe that’s why so many of the novels we love most, from Brontë’s “Jane Eyre” to Rowling’s Harry Potter series, feature some version of this small person. We are gutted not by Scout or Jem in “To Kill a Mockingbird,” but by Dill, the fatherless fantabulist; we may admire Sara Crewe when she’s a kind little heiress, but she’s truly a princess when she loses both her money and her dad. I’ll read anything that features an invisible, unloved child, an orphan either in reality or spirit, more resourceful than any wee one should have to be. Bonus points if the child finds ways to skirt the law. (I’m looking at you, Addie Pray.)

headline.print_headline: The Grifters

abstract: Dr. Li helped show a skeptical medical establishment that a dominant gene, passed from parent to child, was predisposing family members to various cancers.
snippet: Dr. Li helped show a skeptical medical establishment that a dominant gene, passed from parent to child, was predisposing family members to various cancers.
lead_paragraph: Dr. Frederick P. Li, who helped prove to a doubting medical establishment that heredity and genetics play a major role in some forms of cancer, died on June 12 at his home in Brookline, Mass. He was 75.

abstract: Here was my father, giver of values, such as they were.
snippet: Here was my father, giver of values, such as they were.
lead_paragraph: BERKELEY, CALIF. — During a recent trip to Los Angeles, a traffic jam forced me to reroute through Culver City. How could I not take a few minutes to see what had become of 10136 Venice Boulevard?

abstract: Ms. Charren, whose work ultimately led to the Children’s Television Act, received a Peabody Award for public service and, later, a Presidential Medal of Freedom.
snippet: Ms. Charren, whose work ultimately led to the Children’s Television Act, received a Peabody Award for public service and, later, a Presidential Medal of Freedom.
lead_paragraph: Peggy Charren, whose advocacy of higher-minded television programming for children took the issue to government agencies and the halls of Congress and led to landmark legislation, died on Thursday at her home in Dedham, Mass. She was 86.

abstract: As insurers seek to curb losses, many states have been approving large increases in premiums for older policies, but there are ways to cope.
snippet: As insurers seek to curb losses, many states have been approving large increases in premiums for older policies, but there are ways to cope.
lead_paragraph: New York consumers are among the latest to receive word of double-digit increases in the premiums they must pay to keep their insurance coverage for long-term care.

headline.main: Managing the Costs of Long-Term Care Insurance

abstract: The number of veterans on waiting lists of one month or more is now 50 percent higher than it was during the height of last year’s problems.
snippet: The number of veterans on waiting lists of one month or more is now 50 percent higher than it was during the height of last year’s problems.
lead_paragraph: One year after outrage about long waiting lists for health care shook the Department of Veterans Affairs, the agency is facing a new crisis: The number of veterans on waiting lists of one month or more is now 50 percent higher than it was during the height of last year’s problems, department officials say. The department is also facing a nearly $3 billion budget shortfall, which could affect care for many veterans.

abstract: Writing as Harry Brandt, Richard Price follows characters, many of them New York detectives, haunted by, and hunting for, unpunished criminals.
snippet: Writing as Harry Brandt, Richard Price follows characters, many of them New York detectives, haunted by, and hunting for, unpunished criminals.
lead_paragraph: “The Whites,” the title of Richard Price’s riveting new novel, is a reference to the great white whale in “Moby-Dick” — a book that seems to be a kind of touchstone for the author (writing here under the pen name Harry Brandt), having popped up, at least glancingly, in such earlier novels as “Clockers” and “Freedomland.” This time, the parallels to Melville’s classic are beyond obvious: All of the story’s main characters are haunted by something terrible that happened in the past, and all are obsessed with hunting down their nemeses.

abstract: Cognitive changes make it more difficult to meet life’s demands, but while there’s no going back, there are ways of fighting a decline.
snippet: Cognitive changes make it more difficult to meet life’s demands, but while there’s no going back, there are ways of fighting a decline.
lead_paragraph: I recently told my 70s-something walking group that I wanted to write about “retrieval disorder,” our shared problem with remembering names and dates, what we had just read and where, even what we had for dinner last night. Or, in my case, the subject of the column I wrote the day before.

abstract: A look back at Al Hirschfeld’s 80-year career depicting film and theater’s signature faces.
snippet: A look back at Al Hirschfeld’s 80-year career depicting film and theater’s signature faces.
lead_paragraph: When I finished reading “The Hirschfeld Century: Portrait of an Artist and His Age,” I cried.

abstract: This comedy-drama by Stephen Karam traces the connections and tensions in a Pennsylvania clan that is assembling in Manhattan for a holiday dinner.
snippet: This comedy-drama by Stephen Karam traces the connections and tensions in a Pennsylvania clan that is assembling in Manhattan for a holiday dinner.
lead_paragraph: A middle-class family seems to be spiraling toward perilous entropy in “The Humans,” the blisteringly funny, bruisingly sad and altogether wonderful play by Stephen Karam that opened on Sunday at the Laura Pels Theater, in a superlative Roundabout Theater Company production.

abstract: Arbour, who played in the N.H.L. as a defenseman, took over the Islanders in 1973, after they lost 60 games, and led them to four consecutive Stanley Cup titles, from 1980 to 1983.
snippet: Arbour, who played in the N.H.L. as a defenseman, took over the Islanders in 1973, after they lost 60 games, and led them to four consecutive Stanley Cup titles, from 1980 to 1983.
lead_paragraph: Al Arbour, who coached the New York Islanders to four consecutive Stanley Cup championships in the 1980s and finished his career with the second-most coaching wins in National Hockey League history, died on Friday in Sarasota, Fla. He was 82.

abstract: Exploiters are increasingly taking financial advantage of older adults, often through investments, contracts or other fraud.
snippet: Exploiters are increasingly taking financial advantage of older adults, often through investments, contracts or other fraud.
lead_paragraph: It was only after Mariana Cooper, a widow in Seattle, found herself with strained finances that she confessed to her granddaughter that she was afraid she had been bilked out of much of her savings.

headline.main: Financial Abuse of the Elderly: Sometimes Unnoticed, Always Predatory
headline.print_headline: A Hidden Scourge: Preying on the Elderly

abstract: Patients and their families facing disease and death are increasingly using social media tools to share updates and commiseration, as well as to raise caregiving support.
snippet: Patients and their families facing disease and death are increasingly using social media tools to share updates and commiseration, as well as to raise caregiving support.
lead_paragraph: Frank Vardeman was about to undergo knee surgery in January when, as he recalled, his legs suddenly “turned to wet noodles” that could no longer support him. Tests revealed that the culprit was a large growth entangled in his spinal cord, compressing the nerves that control lower parts of his body. It took two neurosurgeries at a Chicago hospital to remove the mass and 44 days of rehab before Mr. Vardeman, 62, could return to his home in Chesterton, Ind.

abstract: Alumni from the payments company have established a reputation as the best in Silicon Valley at finding and funding the latest hot product or company.
snippet: Alumni from the payments company have established a reputation as the best in Silicon Valley at finding and funding the latest hot product or company.
lead_paragraph: The ride-hailing app Uber, the apartment rental site Airbnb and other darlings of the next generation of Silicon Valley start-ups are reshaping the way people use the web. They are also changing expectations about just how much money private companies can raise while still staying out of the public markets.

headline.print_headline: Remembrance of Things Lost

abstract: A new biography of Gore Vidal, novelist, playwright, screenwriter, social and political player.
snippet: A new biography of Gore Vidal, novelist, playwright, screenwriter, social and political player.
lead_paragraph: Easily the best, most entertaining book about Gore Vidal is his 1995 memoir “Palimpsest.” But with the possible exception of “In Bed With Gore Vidal,” Tim Teeman’s 2013 tell-all, “Palimpsest” is also the least reliable of the Vidal books. Vidal was a tireless self-mythologizer, and as his title suggests, that book is a layering of rememberings, re-rememberings and mis-rememberings. In his new, much sounder biography, “Empire of Self,” Jay Parini suggests that even the account of Vidal’s idyllic romance with his high school friend Jimmie Trimble, one of the touchstones of “Palimpsest” — the story of a love so perfect and unearthly that it could never be duplicated — was most likely a fabrication.

abstract: Debates about the validity of A.D.H.D. and the drugs used to treat it — the same that have long polarized Americans — are now playing out all over the world.
snippet: Debates about the validity of A.D.H.D. and the drugs used to treat it — the same that have long polarized Americans — are now playing out all over the world.
lead_paragraph: Last year, Sinan Sonmezler of Istanbul refused to keep going to school. His eighth-grade classmates called him “weird” and “stupid,” and his teachers rebuked him for his tendency to stare out the window during class. The school director told his parents he was “lazy.”

headline.print_headline: A.D.H.D. Rises, but Support Lags

abstract: A new study finds that bringing blood pressure down below current recommendations may greatly reduce the risk of heart attack and stroke.
snippet: A new study finds that bringing blood pressure down below current recommendations may greatly reduce the risk of heart attack and stroke.
lead_paragraph: Declaring they had “potentially lifesaving information,” federal health officials said on Friday that they were ending a major study more than a year early because it has already conclusively answered a question cardiologists have puzzled over for decades: How low should blood pressure go?

abstract: In Evison’s fourth novel, a 78-year-old widow finds out she’s won a free cruise.
snippet: In Evison’s fourth novel, a 78-year-old widow finds out she’s won a free cruise.
lead_paragraph: It’s been more than 50 years since “This Is Your Life,” the early reality show after which Jonathan Evison’s new novel is named, aired the final episode of its initial television run. The concept of the program might seem quaint to the generation that grew up on the Internet — the host, Ralph Edwards, would surprise his guests (some celebrities, some not) with a retrospective of their lives, accompanied by special appearances from friends and family members out of their pasts.

abstract: A father and daughter pursue riches in the music world and on the open water in Daniel Handler’s comic novel.
snippet: A father and daughter pursue riches in the music world and on the open water in Daniel Handler’s comic novel.
lead_paragraph: “Don’t start with Gwen,” begins the second chapter of Daniel Handler’s new novel, “We Are Pirates.” “Don’t start” means “Don’t begin” but also “Don’t mess with,” because the Gwen in question is a furious 14-year-old girl who has just been caught shoplifting. Her mother has “ransacked” her room and “thrown all her stuff out, thinking it was stolen. Well, it was stolen now.” Gwen, you see, is ­upset, so don’t start with Gwen — the joke being, of course, that Chapter 2 is starting with her. The novel itself starts with the report of how the novel’s narrator meets Gwen’s father:

abstract: Ingenues aren’t quite out. But actors in their 70s and 80s are unexpectedly strong contenders in this year’s races.
snippet: Ingenues aren’t quite out. But actors in their 70s and 80s are unexpectedly strong contenders in this year’s races.
lead_paragraph: Most actors would yip with joy if an Oscar-winning director were to ring them up offering a starring role. But not Michael Caine, whose first thought — so he said — when he found himself in that very spot last year was that the director, Paolo Sorrentino, had gone a bit barmy.

abstract: Mr. Mankell was considered the dean of the so-called Scandinavian noir writers who gained fame for novels that mixed suspense with flawed, compelling protagonists and strong social themes.
snippet: Mr. Mankell was considered the dean of the so-called Scandinavian noir writers who gained fame for novels that mixed suspense with flawed, compelling protagonists and strong social themes.
lead_paragraph: Henning Mankell, the Swedish novelist and playwright best known for police procedurals that were translated into a score of languages and sold by the millions throughout the world, died on Monday in Goteborg, Sweden. He was 67.

headline.main: Henning Mankell, Writer Whose Wallander Patrolled a Gritty Sweden, Dies at 67
headline.print_headline: Henning Mankell, Swedish Author, Is Dead at 67

abstract: Almost two million Americans over age 65 rarely or never leave their homes. They are more likely to be minority women, and in poor health.
snippet: Almost two million Americans over age 65 rarely or never leave their homes. They are more likely to be minority women, and in poor health.
lead_paragraph: What she mourns most, says Solange DeLaPaz, are the mundane pleasures and rituals of her once-active life. A weekly manicure at the corner nail salon. Saturday excursions to Macy’s shoe department.

headline.main: At Home, Many Seniors Are Imprisoned by Their Independence
headline.print_headline: Imprisoned by Independence

abstract: Mr. Karam, who specializes in agonizing comedies that are funnier than their subjects would indicate, has a new play, “The Humans,” that can also be viewed as a horror story.
snippet: Mr. Karam, who specializes in agonizing comedies that are funnier than their subjects would indicate, has a new play, “The Humans,” that can also be viewed as a horror story.
lead_paragraph: The playwright Stephen Karam has short dark hair, bright dark eyes and a wide smile that occasionally overpowers the rest of his face like some sudden, bloodless coup. On a recent morning at a cafe near his Chinatown apartment in New York, he was eating a red pepper and spinach omelet, a brave attempt to add more vegetables to his diet. At 35, he still looks boyish, and when he talks about being a grown-up, it takes a few seconds to realize that he is actually talking about himself.

abstract: How the novel “Emma” helped me cope with my mother’s decline.
snippet: How the novel “Emma” helped me cope with my mother’s decline.
lead_paragraph: I CAME to Jane Austen’s “Emma” in my 50s, which is late for many Austen aficionados. The story of a wealthy 21-year-old woman who lives with her father and imagines herself a matchmaker hadn’t caught my attention until then. At first, I was made uneasy by Emma as she imagines romance where it isn’t and misses it where it is. But during a caregiving crisis in my life, I lost count of how many times I read or listened to Austen’s novel. I turned her words over in my mind like a piece of slowly melting hard candy.

abstract: We condemn lies, but tell them every day. The philosopher Gerald Dworkin invites readers to explain when it is right to lie, and why.
snippet: We condemn lies, but tell them every day. The philosopher Gerald Dworkin invites readers to explain when it is right to lie, and why.
lead_paragraph: Most of us believe that lying is wrong. We teach our children that it is wrong, and hope or expect that value judgment is shared by our friends and family. In public, we decry politicians and public officials when they lie, which we have frequent occasion to do these days. But the truth about lying is more complicated.

headline.main: Are These 10 Lies Justified?

abstract: Mr. Fowler waited four decades to publicly acknowledge his role in Jimmie Lee Jackson’s death, considered an impetus for the 1965 voting-rights marches from Selma to Montgomery.
snippet: Mr. Fowler waited four decades to publicly acknowledge his role in Jimmie Lee Jackson’s death, considered an impetus for the 1965 voting-rights marches from Selma to Montgomery.
lead_paragraph: Jimmie Lee Jackson, a 26-year-old laborer and church deacon, was shot to death in Mack’s Cafe in Marion, Ala., on the night of Feb. 18, 1965, and the killing proved historic: It provoked the fateful voting-rights march from Selma to Montgomery, turning the tide for the civil rights movement.

abstract: We’re getting older. Our health care policies have to keep pace.
snippet: We’re getting older. Our health care policies have to keep pace.
lead_paragraph: The 50th anniversary of Medicare next month is an opportunity to consider what the goals of medicine should be in our aging society and how we want to live in relation to medicine’s evolving tools.

abstract: Two adventurers, unafraid of winter, marry in an ice hotel as a blizzard bears down.
snippet: Two adventurers, unafraid of winter, marry in an ice hotel as a blizzard bears down.
lead_paragraph: It’s hard to avoid the irony: A woman who thwarted her boyfriend’s plan for a marriage proposal because of the cold is married in a chapel made of snow and ice in Quebec, with a blizzard as a bonus.

headline.main: Cold Enough to Warm the Heart
headline.print_headline: Cold Enough to Warm the Heart

abstract: Whether as volunteers or for profit, older adults are finding time to solve everyday problems.
snippet: Whether as volunteers or for profit, older adults are finding time to solve everyday problems.
lead_paragraph: LIKE many inventors, Bob Nepper, 82, is a compulsive improver. Mr. Nepper, an electrical engineer who lives in North St. Paul, Minn., has pet projects that have included a self-guided lawn mower and an outside faucet that can run hot and cold. His basement is stocked with tools like a lathe and a milling machine to craft his ideas.

headline.print_headline: The Grandparents of Invention

abstract: With his performance of “We Shall Overcome” at the inaugural meeting of the Student Nonviolent Coordinating Committee in 1960, Mr. Carawan turned a little-known folk song into an anthem.
snippet: With his performance of “We Shall Overcome” at the inaugural meeting of the Student Nonviolent Coordinating Committee in 1960, Mr. Carawan turned a little-known folk song into an anthem.
lead_paragraph: On an April night in 1960, Guy Carawan stood before a group of black students in Raleigh, N.C., and sang a little-known folk song. With that single stroke, he created an anthem that would echo into history, sung at the Selma-to-Montgomery marches of 1965, in apartheid-era South Africa, in international demonstrations in support of the Tiananmen Square protesters, at the dismantled Berlin Wall and beyond.

headline.print_headline: Guy Carawan, Who Found a Way to Overcome, With Song, Dies at 87

abstract: Mrs. Nicholson was just 25 when she won a sports bet that paid more than £150,000, the equivalent today of about $4.5 million, and her life inspired a musical and a BBC television film.
snippet: Mrs. Nicholson was just 25 when she won a sports bet that paid more than £150,000, the equivalent today of about $4.5 million, and her life inspired a musical and a BBC television film.
lead_paragraph: She went to London to collect her prize wearing borrowed stockings and cardboard in the soles of her shoes. There, as flashbulbs exploded, she became an international celebrity — the factory worker who had come into a fortune.

abstract: Older adults with diabetes and other chronic conditions should be treated less aggressively than they commonly are, some experts say.
snippet: Older adults with diabetes and other chronic conditions should be treated less aggressively than they commonly are, some experts say.
lead_paragraph: Over many years, the 77-year-old patient has managed to control his Type 2 diabetes. Thanks in part to daily doses of a drug that reduces blood sugar, his hemoglobin A1c (an average measure of recent blood glucose control) is a very low 6.5 percent.

abstract: No play opening on Broadway this fall has had a more fraught back story, though star power always guaranteed a commercial slam dunk.
snippet: No play opening on Broadway this fall has had a more fraught back story, though star power always guaranteed a commercial slam dunk.
lead_paragraph: No matter what his salary is, it seems safe to say that Christopher Denham is the most underpaid actor on Broadway. Mr. Denham — a young man with, I sincerely hope, a very resilient nervous system — is one of a cast of two in “China Doll,” the saggy new play by David Mamet that was finally opened to critics on Wednesday night at the Gerald Schoenfeld Theater, and he is onstage for almost the entire show.

abstract: While it is far preferable for retirees to remain at home as they age, the choices and costs can be daunting.
snippet: While it is far preferable for retirees to remain at home as they age, the choices and costs can be daunting.
lead_paragraph: GIVEN the tens of millions of people in retirement or about to enter it, it’s surprising how few plan for something most of them will eventually need: help doing basic tasks at home. But perhaps it is not so surprising: It’s like learning a difficult new language late in life.

headline.main: Learning the Unfamiliar Language of Home Care
headline.print_headline: The Unfamiliar Language of Home Care

abstract: Older patients without anyone to make medical decisions on their behalf are described as unbefriended. In a crisis, there is no one to speak for them.
snippet: Older patients without anyone to make medical decisions on their behalf are described as unbefriended. In a crisis, there is no one to speak for them.
lead_paragraph: The unconscious man in his 90s was brought to an emergency room where Dr. Douglas White was a critical care physician. The staff couldn’t find any relatives to make medical decisions on his behalf.

abstract: A career filled with tough cases transforms a lawyer into a champion for the elderly, just like her mother.
snippet: A career filled with tough cases transforms a lawyer into a champion for the elderly, just like her mother.
lead_paragraph: In the midst of my raging adolescence in 1979, my mother was devoting most of her time to a Jewish nursing home in Baltimore where she was the board president.

headline.main: Coming Full Circle to Help Her Elders

abstract: After a young rugby player died in Northern Ireland, his family and a brain expert set about to establish concussion guidelines.
snippet: After a young rugby player died in Northern Ireland, his family and a brain expert set about to establish concussion guidelines.
lead_paragraph: ROSEWELL, Scotland — At the end of a nearly three-year investigation filled with his frustration and suspicion toward headmasters, coaches and the police, Peter Robinson finally heard the verdict that he feared: His 14-year-old son, Benjamin, had died after being hit in the head multiple times during a rugby match in which he should have been pulled from the field.

abstract: Nearly 20 years and more than 100 pounds ago, Ryan Hoffman was a hulking offensive lineman for North Carolina. He ended up a panhandler plagued with short-term memory problems and other troubles.
snippet: Nearly 20 years and more than 100 pounds ago, Ryan Hoffman was a hulking offensive lineman for North Carolina. He ended up a panhandler plagued with short-term memory problems and other troubles.
lead_paragraph: LAKELAND, Fla. — With sunset minutes away, the man in the neon yellow knit hat took his usual spot here at a busy intersection. Across from a Publix supermarket and on the edge of a Circle K parking lot, he sat against a streetlight holding a worn cardboard sign with dirt-stained hands that could easily palm a basketball.

abstract: In dozens of emails unearthed by hackers, Sony Pictures executives and others discussed altering the script and marketing the movie more as a whistle-blower story than as a condemnation of the N.F.L.
snippet: In dozens of emails unearthed by hackers, Sony Pictures executives and others discussed altering the script and marketing the movie more as a whistle-blower story than as a condemnation of the N.F.L.
lead_paragraph: When Sony Pictures Entertainment decided to make a movie focusing on the death and dementia professional football players have endured from repeated hits to the head — and the N.F.L.’s efforts toward a cover-up — it signed Will Smith to star as one of the first scientists to disclose the problem. It named the film bluntly, “Concussion.”

abstract: Mr. Donovan is the favorite to replace Representative Michael G. Grimm, despite criticism of the way he handled Eric Garner’s chokehold inquiry on Staten Island.
snippet: Mr. Donovan is the favorite to replace Representative Michael G. Grimm, despite criticism of the way he handled Eric Garner’s chokehold inquiry on Staten Island.
lead_paragraph: In the span of a few months, Daniel M. Donovan Jr. has been swept from relative obscurity into the center of New York City politics.

abstract: A family’s cooking history is seasoned with smudges, shorthand notations and challenging penmanship.
snippet: A family’s cooking history is seasoned with smudges, shorthand notations and challenging penmanship.
lead_paragraph: The last full sentence I heard from my mom was around Easter. “You better call Michael,” she said.

abstract: After a bad batch of the drug Molly sent 12 people to the hospital last month, Wesleyan University has been trying to balance open-mindedness with student safety.
snippet: After a bad batch of the drug Molly sent 12 people to the hospital last month, Wesleyan University has been trying to balance open-mindedness with student safety.
lead_paragraph: MIDDLETOWN, Conn. — When a Wesleyan University student who had taken drugs at a party last month began feeling ill, his friends took him to his dorm room, gave him water and Triscuits, and assumed he just needed to sleep it off.

abstract: I saved her voice mails, realizing that any message could be the last.
snippet: I saved her voice mails, realizing that any message could be the last.
lead_paragraph: ANN ARBOR — I had two saved messages, and both began the same way: “Hello, Rebecca. This is your grandmother. In Florida.”

abstract: The couple’s five-second appearance in the presidential campaign announcement video spread news of their wedding plans.
snippet: The couple’s five-second appearance in the presidential campaign announcement video spread news of their wedding plans.
lead_paragraph: It may have been Hillary Rodham Clinton who put the couple’s marriage plans on the map by including Jared Milrad and Nathan Johnson in her videotaped presidential campaign announcement, but it was a big, floppy dog that helped seal their relationship.

abstract: After some notable previous revelations proved true, Britain is now taking each new case seriously and engaging in a systemic review.
snippet: After some notable previous revelations proved true, Britain is now taking each new case seriously and engaging in a systemic review.
lead_paragraph: LONDON — Accusations of child sexual abuse against some prominent figures of Britain’s recent past have proved true. Allegations of similar wrongdoing by others, dating back decades, surface regularly now in the hothouse British press, as does talk of cover-ups by some of the nation’s most powerful institutions.

abstract: Joseph Buffey pleaded guilty to rape, even though there was forensic evidence showing he didn’t commit the crime. Should prosecutors have been required to share it with him?
snippet: Joseph Buffey pleaded guilty to rape, even though there was forensic evidence showing he didn’t commit the crime. Should prosecutors have been required to share it with him?
lead_paragraph: Next week, the West Virginia Supreme Court will hear a case in which 30 former prosecutors from around the country have taken the unusual step of siding with the defense. It’s a battle over a DNA test, and whether prosecutors must turn the results over to a defendant when they point to his innocence — even if he has made the decision to plead guilty.

headline.main: Who Should Have Access to DNA Evidence?

abstract: More than 58 million Americans take medicines to lower blood pressure, reducing their risk of heart attack and stroke. But experts aren’t certain how low blood pressure should go.
snippet: More than 58 million Americans take medicines to lower blood pressure, reducing their risk of heart attack and stroke. But experts aren’t certain how low blood pressure should go.
lead_paragraph: Almost half a century after rigorous studies showed medicines that lower blood pressure prevent heart attacks, strokes and deaths, researchers still do not know just how low blood pressure should go. More than 58 million Americans take these drugs, but this fundamental question remains unresolved.

abstract: As MediaStorm celebrates 10 years, its founder looks ahead to the challenges and opportunities facing photographers in the online world.
snippet: As MediaStorm celebrates 10 years, its founder looks ahead to the challenges and opportunities facing photographers in the online world.
lead_paragraph: Brian Storm was raised in the Detroit area and attended the College of the Ozarks on a baseball scholarship. While obtaining a graduate degree at the University of Missouri’s School of Journalism in 1993, he discovered computers and began making interactive CD-ROM disks. He started a company, MediaStorm, but put it on hold while working for MSNBC and Corbis over the next decade.He relaunched MediaStorm in 2005 as a film-production company and interactive design studio, which this month celebrates its 10th anniversary. He spoke with James Estrin about the future of photography and multimedia. Their conversation has been edited.

abstract: At 46, Marilyn Manson, with a career as a best-selling goth rock star and agitator behind him, is facing a bit of an identity crisis.
snippet: At 46, Marilyn Manson, with a career as a best-selling goth rock star and agitator behind him, is facing a bit of an identity crisis.
lead_paragraph: WEST HOLLYWOOD, Calif. — “We’re drinking wodka,” Marilyn Manson said, pronouncing the word like he was a fur-hatted Russian cartoon character, and filling a tumbler. Two tumblers: Like any peacocking musician, he knew that a drinking buddy makes for a ready audience.

abstract: A New York State statute to protect the infirm has become a routine tool for nursing homes to ensure bills are paid.
snippet: A New York State statute to protect the infirm has become a routine tool for nursing homes to ensure bills are paid.
lead_paragraph: Lillian Palermo tried to prepare for the worst possibilities of aging. An insurance executive with a Ph.D. in psychology and a love of ballroom dancing, she arranged for her power of attorney and health care proxy to go to her husband, Dino, eight years her junior, if she became incapacitated. And in her 80s, she did.

abstract: Forced individual arbitration often bears little resemblance to court: The rules tend to favor businesses, and judges and juries are replaced by arbitrators whose rulings are difficult to appeal.
snippet: Forced individual arbitration often bears little resemblance to court: The rules tend to favor businesses, and judges and juries are replaced by arbitrators whose rulings are difficult to appeal.
lead_paragraph: Deborah L. Pierce, an emergency room doctor in Philadelphia, was optimistic when she brought a sex discrimination claim against the medical group that had dismissed her. Respected by colleagues, she said she had a stack of glowing evaluations and evidence that the practice had a pattern of denying women partnerships.

abstract: The poet and writer, shellshocked after World War I, found a place to write in a village on the northern coast of the Spanish island.

abstract: Dr. Sacks explored some of the brain’s strangest pathways in best-selling case histories like “The Man Who Mistook His Wife for a Hat,” achieving a level of renown rare among scientists.
snippet: Dr. Sacks explored some of the brain’s strangest pathways in best-selling case histories like “The Man Who Mistook His Wife for a Hat,” achieving a level of renown rare among scientists.
lead_paragraph: Oliver Sacks, the neurologist and acclaimed author who explored some of the brain’s strangest pathways in best-selling case histories like “The Man Who Mistook His Wife for a Hat,” using his patients’ disorders as starting points for eloquent meditations on consciousness and the human condition, died on Sunday at his home in Manhattan. He was 82.

abstract: Powell, who played on the L.P.G.A. Tour from 1967 to 1980, experienced racism and received death threats. Now she’s one of the first female members of the Royal and Ancient Golf Club in Scotland.
snippet: Powell, who played on the L.P.G.A. Tour from 1967 to 1980, experienced racism and received death threats. Now she’s one of the first female members of the Royal and Ancient Golf Club in Scotland.
lead_paragraph: An unexpected gift arrived last December at the public golf course that Renee Powell’s father carved out of an old dairy farm in East Canton, Ohio. Interspersed with holiday mail was an envelope with a Scotland postmark. Inside was a letter of invitation for Powell to become one of the first seven female members of the Royal and Ancient Golf Club in St. Andrews, known as the home of golf.

abstract: Ten years after Herbert Warren Wind’s death, few can identify him as the man who introduced “Amen Corner” to golf lexicon. Ben Crenshaw, though, playing in his final Masters, remembers Wind well.
snippet: Ten years after Herbert Warren Wind’s death, few can identify him as the man who introduced “Amen Corner” to golf lexicon. Ben Crenshaw, though, playing in his final Masters, remembers Wind well.
lead_paragraph: The whorl of wind will be easier to negotiate than the swirl of memories this week when Ben Crenshaw plays the 11th, 12th and 13th holes at the Masters for the final time in his fabled career.

abstract: People age 85 and above are one of the city’s fastest growing groups, but they are almost invisible. Six New Yorkers share their stories of love, pain and abrupt change.
snippet: People age 85 and above are one of the city’s fastest growing groups, but they are almost invisible. Six New Yorkers share their stories of love, pain and abrupt change.
lead_paragraph: It was an average week in an aging city. Frederick Jones, 88, fell in the kitchen of his Crown Heights apartment and went to sleep on the floor, resting until he felt strong enough to pull himself up. Ping Wong, 90, told her daughter that she could not make their annual spring trip to Atlantic City — the drive was too long, her back and joints too sore. Helen Moses, 90, decorated an enameled copper pin for the man who lives two doors down in their Bronx nursing home. He held her hand in a loving squeeze.

abstract: My 20-year struggle with bipolar disorder.
snippet: My 20-year struggle with bipolar disorder.
lead_paragraph: The manila folder is full of faded faxes. The top sheet contains a brief description of my first medically confirmed manic episode, more than 20 years ago, when I was admitted as a teenager to U.C.L.A.’s Neuropsychiatric Institute: “Increased psychomotor rate, decreased need for sleep (about two to three hours a night), racing thoughts and paranoid ideation regarding her parents following her and watching her, as well as taping the phone calls that she was making.”
